deck_excerpt: Magnet Warriors , Adamancipators, and Fossils all come together to fill the board up with negation effects and strong Rock monsters.
deck_description: This deck is compatible with running with just Berserkion at the fore front, Or Crystal Wing leading the pack. It's taken a minute but I believe I've finally built a formidable magnet warrior deck.     First of Adamancipators are still great, by removing block dragon I couldn't put one of the best rock searches in here. But adamancipators and magnet warriors go hand in hand when it comes to searching for the monsters that you need to win the game. It only takes a matter of timewhich isnt something we always have today in the Yu-Gi-Oh world, but oh well right? I recently seen on someone else's decklist that Fossil's and Magnet Warriors work well together. The Adamancipators take care of filling up the field and Fossils use the discarded rock monsters as fusion materials to create a quick gate way to a great rock monster. Depending on which monster you'll be able to summon, you can gain some effects that'll give you the upper hand.     Starting of with all four magnet warriors in your hand isn't an issue, Its actually right where I would wanna be. Magnet tip: Do not summon berserkion right away. Take your time. Use Gamma to summon Delta and send the other beta to the grave. Beta is an amazing card but its very easy to search your warriors in this deck so he's as much needed as usual. Now during your opponents turn you want to use Gamma's effect to summon another Delta from the deck in defensive position, hint hint, most of the rock monsters you summon will be in defense. Then use that Delta to send the other Gamma. Now if your opponent destroys one of your Deltas. You can use his effect to summon Valkyrion from the deck and boom easy hit stick to have on the field for protection. Next turn summon Berserkion now you have them both until either you get poly or find a way to get yourself out of trouble (if you're in any.)     Now if you start off with Admancipators and a Weathering Soldier. Do your best not to use the weathering solider unless you already have Fossil Fusion. The Adama's mill effect will more than likely find another weathering solider. It's better to start of with a level 2 tuner so that you can have the opportunity to go into crystal wing. Synchro summon Raptite to searching ANY rock monsters instead of Leonite's Adama card effect.     My current best combo is CrystalWing and Imperion's effects. Just those two alone stop my opponents whole push. Two gameciels so that you can have extra options for WATER monsters in the grave for Dragite effect. Naturia Beast mills everytime to stop spell cards, Gorgonic Guardian negates monster effects, Stardust Dragon negates destruction effects.     Left A Very Detailed Explanation for the beginners, Vets will understand this combo easy. Please let me know how you feel about the deck in the comments! Let me know what other things you try!

deck_excerpt: An Evilswarm control deck, that has a simple game-plan (summoning Evilswarm Ophion) while supporting it with floodgates and other backrow cards.
deck_description:
With this deck your main goal is to go first and set up Evilswarm Ophion ( by summoning 2 Evilswarm monsters), which searches Infestation Pandemic to keep him alive, and set some backrow. Pros & Cons Pros of playing the deck:
  • The gameplan is really simplistic, which helps avoiding any mistakes in gameplay
  • The Floodgate effect of Evilswarm Ophion is still very strong (but very meta dependent though)
  • Evilswarm has an inbuilt protection against easy main deck Outs, as it can search its own Spell/Trap protection while also making your opponent unable to summon Kaijus/Pankratops/etc
  • 'There can only be one' and 'Dimension Shifter' nearly hit every deck, so being able o play them without any downside speaks for this deck
  • The deck is not reliant on the graveyard and doesn't search often ( usually 1 time for Infection Pandemic and that's it)
  • The deck also isn't really reliant for on field monster effects to go through (Evilswarm Castor's additional summon effect can't be negated with effect Veiler /etc and Rescue rabbit banishes for cost)
  • The deck can easily be sided for a match up, as the spots for backrow-cards are not fixed
  • in a meta, that isnt dominated by combo decks , your gameplan can catch many people off guard
  • The deck leaves a lot of free extra deck space that can be filled with any targets you find helpful
  Cons of playing the deck:
  • 'Ash Blossom & Jouyous Spring' or 'PSY-Framegear Gamma' can hit hard against Rescue Rabbit / Ghost Ogre on ophion's search effect also is hard to play against ( notice that if you activated Dimension Shifter, Ghost Ogre can't be activated as it has to be send to the Graveyard; also when Ophion hits the field, PSY-Framegear Gama is turned off)
  •  If you are playing against Link based decks, your backrow mostly is your only hope
  • while Going second, your tools for winning are very limited
  • As this deck only plays a few monster negates ( 3 Solemn Strike/ 3 Forbidden Chalice gives a 57% chane to draw at least 1, not counting the potential of Allure of Darkness to draw further through your deck), match-ups against decks with inbuilt backrow removal are very draw dependent.
  Card Ratios & Explaination Main Deck
  • 3 Evilswarm Heliotrope: We have to play 3 in order to maximize the chance that Rescue Rabbit is live (the chance to draw 2 or more copies of Heliotrope is 3,6%), also It's not as bricky as someone might think, as we can summon it with Evilswarm Castor's effect, use it for Allure of Darkness or just reshuffle it into the deck with Infestation Infection ( besides using it for Rescue Rabbit and Unexpected Dai)
  • 3 Evilswarm Castor: It's additional summon effect lets you play around every Hand Trap as it can't be negated
  • 3 Rescue Rabbit: The perfect enabler for the deck, even if its weak against Ash and Gamma
  • 3 Evilswarm Mandragora: We need targets for Evilswarm Kerykeion/ Castor/ Infestation Infection, also it can be helful going 2nd ( special summoning this plus normal summoning any lvl 4 monster is already a Rank 4 Xyz)
  • 3 Dimension Shifter: Insanely strong Hand Trap, that can be good going first and 2nd (you literally always use it, exeptyou draw it as your 6t card and need fodder for Allure of Darkness)
  • 2 Evilswarm Kerykeion: Its a good Mid-Game centered card, but you really want to see other cards in your opening hand ( 2 copies might come up in he long run, also it's a target for Castor)
  • 1 Evilswarm Castor: Spell/Trap removal that tributes for cost can be useful in niche scenarios, if not, it's at least another Evilswarm Target
  • 3 Unexpected Dai: Works as a good starter/ bait for Ash; if you draw more that 1 copy you could set it as a bait for upcoming backrow removal
  • 3 Allure of Darkness: The deck plays 15 dark monsters and desperately needs a way to unbrick some hands/ swich unused monsters to potential backrow (an extra copy of Dimension Shifter is a good example)
  • 3 Forbidden Chalice: Good going 1st and second; can be activated in the Damage Step
  • 1 Reinforcement of the Army: Searches Evilswarm Castor
  • 1 Infestation Pandemic: Helps keeping your Ophion (a)live, you usually search this with Ophion ( some people play more than 1, I tend to keep an extra copy in the side deck for consistency reasons)
  • 1 Double or Nothing: We have to play this Brick in order to quickly close out games with the Utopia Double package
  • 3 Solemn Strike: Good ging 1st and still useful going 2nd, as you can't chain on it with spell speed 2 (one might swap it for Solemn Judgement for backrow protection, but I'd rather keep that in the side deck)
  • 3 There can only be One: This floodgate + Ophion forms a lock that is kind of hard to break for a lot of decks, the only downside is that you can't follow up with utopia double/ Rescue Rabbit ( it only summons 1 Heliotrope from the deck instead of 2)
  • 3 Crackdown: An insanely good card for simplyfied gamestates, while our goal is to achive exactly that
  • 1 Infestation Infection: Works as another target for Ophion's search effect, switches unwanted Evilswarm Monsters to useful ones, if Ophion is about to leave the filed you can at least shuffle him back to the Extra Deck in order to not lose card advantage
Extra Deck
  • 2 Evilswarm Ophion: Boss monster of the deck ( you might bump it up to 3, but  in scenarios where that 3rd copy would be useful, you usually lose anyways)
  • 1 Evilswarm Bahamut: as a great effect, but is quite conditional though
  • 1 Utopia Double: For OTKs
  • 1 Utopia the Lightning: For overrunning monsters that can only be killed by battle
  • 1 Utopia: In order to use Utopia Double/the Lightning
  • 1 Tornado Dragon: For Spell/Trap removal
  • 1 Castel, the Skyblaster Musketeer: For Monster removal/ swiching monsters to defense position to overrrun them/ turn off their effects
  • 1 Evilswarm Exciton Knight: Works good going 2nd for board wiping/ even better if you sided in Dark Ruler no more
  • 1 Bagooska the terribly tired Tapir: if you can't OTK in your 3rd turn you usually stall with this + Ophion; this card might be better going 1st in some match ups
  • 1 Abyss Dweller: Good going 1st in some match ups, or for further stalling if you couldn't OTK
  • 1 Underclock Taker: good for linking off stolen monsters/ overruning your enemy
  • 1 Knightmare Phoenix: can link off unused Monsters/ as a back up plan if you already used Tornado Dragon
  • 1 Knightmare Cerberus: can link off unused Monsters/ as a back up plan for Castel
  • 1 Starving Venom Fusion Dragon: I play Super Polymerization in the side deck ( if you don't, play what is suitable for you)
Side Deck
  • 3 Dark Ruler no more: very strong card going 2nd, especially with Excition Knight
  • 3 Super Polymerization: extremely good going 2nd against certain match ups
  • 3 Twin Twister: against Backrow decks/ decks that rely on certain Spell/Trap cards
  • 3 Solemn Judgement: to prepare for upcoming backrow removal of your enemy if going 1st/ to negate  Spell/Traps  that are the core of your enemy's strategy
  • 1 Infestation Pandemic: If you are facing more Spell/Trap hate against your Ophion
  • 1 Imperial Order: against Spell oriented decks
  • 1 Anti-Spell Fragrance:  against Spell oriented decks ( doesn't hurt yourself as much as Imperial Order, in that sense you might switch to 2 Anti-Spell Fragrance and cut Imperial Order)
Non Budget Variants If you aren't playing on a budget( you might also change to a meta deck if that is the case) you probably should swap Allure of Darkness for Pot of Extravagance and rearrange your Extra deck; you should also swap  Forbidden Chalice for Infinite Impermanence; Nibiru/ Forbidden Droplet/Lightning Storm are probably stronger  side Deck options than the cheaper ones I mentioned

deck_excerpt: Kaijius with a Danger! engine and some floodgates.
deck_description: I made a Kaiju deck a while back similar to this, but i'm fairly unhappy with this, so I decided to remake it. Fun fact: Kaijus are one of my favorite archetypes. I adore the entire Kaiju genre so, the archetype itself is something I love. Deck guide? Deck guide. 3x Bigfoot- 3k beater if you get it out, easy card removal if it's discarded. Underappreciated Danger! imo 3x Chupacabra- draw/tribute fodder, and can special summon a discarded Danger! if itself is discarded. 1x Nessie- Would run at more if I could, but it's limited. 28k wall if you get out that's also just draw/tribute fodder, but if discarded, it gives you another Danger! to replace the lost Nessie, which is amazing. 2x Thunderbird- 28k beater if it special summons itself, can remove possible problem cards like Imperm and Fog Blade that your opponent has set otherwise. 1x Jackalope- Yet again, draw/tribute fodder. But if discarded, gives you another Danger! to act as tribute fodder. Fantastic Danger!, it's limited for a reason. 1x Snek Boy- can't spell his name and i'm not gonna try. Adorable card, and it gives you tribute/draw fodder and it's always tribute fodder no matter what, as it special summons itself when discarded. I'm tempted to get one just to frame it because I love this card 1x Pankratops- Easy special summon and monster removal, but can also serve as tribute fodder. 2x Dogoran- tribute monster, 3k beater 3k Gamaciel- Easy monster removal 2x Jizikuru- Fantastic 33k beater with a built in negate 2x Majesty's Fiend- stop playing lol 1x Radian- literally just tribute a monster, either an opponent's or your's, OTK lol 1x Jupiter- Requires two tributes but that's not very hard for this deck, discards two cards which can be Dangers! for their effects, and steals an opponent's monster to become a big beater 1x Pluto- Also two tributes but, hand info and if you somehow guess write ya get a free monster 3x Thunder King- The boss monster. 33k beater, attacks three times on occasion, can OTK with ease 2x Vanity's Fiend- stop playing the game lol 3x Interrupted Kaiju Slumber- Dark Hole combined with a free monster, just give your opponent a Gamaciel and it's free damage and you can go in for an OTK with ease 3x Kyouto Waterfront- Great field spell, racks up counters fast as fuck as you tear through the opponent and get rid of your own cards, can search a Kaiju when neccesary or provide counters for the Kaiju's own effects 3x Pot of Extravagance- fantastic draw power, what else do u want me to say 2x World Legacy Monstrosity- Leads into the occasional Eternity, and thins out your deck. 3x There Can Only Be One- Locks down nearly any deck and stops them from playinh, making them an easy target to OTK The extra deck is just banish fodder, you might wanna link into Linkuribo then Gardna on occasion though, or maybe make an Eternity, but banish the rest Playing guide Deck is a pretty simple OTK based going second deck. You spam out Dangers! and draw if you didn't open with an Interrupted; if you did open an Interrupted, play it and destroy the board, then special summon your Thunder King and a Gamaciel for the opponent. Afterwards, spam Dangers! for tribute fodder, and tribute into either a Kaiju if you didn't use the Interrupted method, or go into a Fiend or beater with tributes. Rack up counters for Thunder King. Afterwards, set There Can Only Be if you opened with it. Attack the opponent, although you probably won't kill them in the first turn. Use the effects of the Fiends and such to make sure they just can't play, then OTK them entirely. Note: Yes, you'll want to go second. If going first, just set up your floodgates and hope. Maybe make an Eternity as well, or a Pluto for hand info before they even start their plays. Fun fact: I'm mostly blind

deck_excerpt: This has slowly became one of my favorite decks to use because of how it can bring out not only strong monsters, but also just the most bad*ss monster
deck_description:
Basic combo
  1. Special Summon Fortress by dumping a level 8 monster or monsters who's levels equal 8. If Megaform or Citadel is in the hand send either one to the graveyard.
  2. Summon Scrap recycler and if Citadel wasn't in the hand, use Scrap recycler's effect to send him to the graveyard
  3. Link summon Scrap Wyvern with Fortress and Recycler
  4. Use Scrap Wyvern's effect to special summon Recycler then immediately send him back to the graveyard
  5. Citadel's effect activates due to Recycler being destroyed by Wyvern's effect and is brought back to the field
  6. Wyvern's second effect activates and special summon Scrap Golem back to the field
  7. If going second, using Wyvern's effect destroy a card on your opponents field. If going first, you would need to destroy a card on your field. Either you could set a spell or trap card and destroy it. At the begging of the combo, if possible you could special summon Machina air raider or Irradiator and destroy them.
  8. Use Golem's effect to bring back Recycler to the field
  9. Then summon any link 4 monster. For budget based deck Unchained Abomination or Borreload
  10. Either OTK or just have a good board setup
Strategies: This deck can bring out a lot of strong extra deck monsters, along with strong main boss monsters. Using Air Raider and Irradiator to special summon them to the field to make a strong rank 8 xyz monster is easy if there are not a lot of resources in the hand. A lot of main deck monsters destroy other monster by effects, this can help bring out Citadel easily through his effect. Machina Possesstorage is a great way to bring out extra deck monsters due to its effect on summon which brings back one machina monster in the graveyard. Possesstorage can also get rid of Spells or traps easily by sending targeting one machina monster you control and one spell or trap card on your opponents field and send them to the hand. This deck can also bring out synchro monsters through Torque Tune Gear. Either use Fortress and Tune Gear to bring out a level 8 synchro or use his effect to equip to a level 4 and synchro summon through that way. The level 8 synchro monster depends on a persons budget.

deck_excerpt: Go second With powerful Blowouts and take full control of Nekroz's powerful effects.
deck_description: Why Go Second In Nekroz?             Nekroz have a surprising number of cards the benefit from going second. Powerful Cards Like Nekroz of Trisula and Nekroz of Brionac only can use their on board effects on an opponent’s already established board. This build takes advantage of two main cards Nekroz of Sophia and Dance Princess of the Nekroz. Nekroz of Sophia lets you discard it and a Nekroz ritual spell to stop your opponent from special summoning from the extra deck during Main Phase 1. Since a player can’t enter battle phase and therefore main phase 2 turn 1, Nekroz of Sophia is electively a hand trap version of Domain of the True Monarchs on turn 1. Also every Nekroz ritual spell lets you banish itself and one Nekroz monster to search another ritual spell, giving you back much needed value when discarded with Nekroz of  Sophia. Dance Princess of the Nekroz is an often underutilized tool that has the following effect on field: “Your opponent cannot activate cards or effects in response to the activation of a "Nekroz" Ritual Spell Card“ And “"Nekroz" Ritual Monsters you control cannot be targeted by an opponent's card effects“. This card lets you play around negates that would stop your ritual summons. Dance Princess of the Nekroz combined with a ritual summon of Nekroz of Unicore can easily disarm your opponent’s monster negates. Its effect when tributed, while not the main reason for its usage in the deck is also relevant allowing for recycling of resources in longer games. It also should be noted that as this card is a level 4 water monster it aids in making Bahamut Shark and then Toadally Awesome. The Deck also utilizes the cards Lava Golem, The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode, and Gizmek Uka, the Festive Fox of Fecundity to help go second. Gizmek Uka is fantastic in this deck as it can punish the usage of the ever popular Cryston Halqifbrax with a summon of both itself and Barrier Statue of the Torrent from deck. Gizmek Uka can also fetch both itself and the two non-ritual Impcantation Monsters if the opponent doesn’t play Cryston Halqifbrax. The Math and Consistency While its not perfect odds, this deck is optimized to have some form of blowout over about 85% of the time. The Deck will simply draw one of Lava Golem, The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode, or Gizmek Uka, the Festive Fox of Fecundity around 78.89% of the time. That’s a healthy base for going second but what else does it have? The deck opens Nekroz of Sophia and a ritual spell in 17.83% of games, that’s about 1 out of every 5 where your opponent cant use their extra deck to set up negates to stop your ritual summons. Outside of these blowouts let’s look at Nekroz’s inherent searchability. 10/42 cards in the deck search another nekroz card with no questions asked. Nekroz of Brionac gets you any Nekroz Monster which gets you Nekroz of Clausolas who in turn gets you any Nekroz Ritual spell. Another 13/42 cards search Nekroz cards with a bit of setup. Due to Nekroz’s heavily search reliant playstyle its very hard to calculate exactly how many negates on average this deck can play through. From personal experience being able to play through 1 negate is almost guaranteed, 2 negates is common enough, and 3 negates can be done with a lucky enough hand. Side Deck and Extra Deck. This deck struggles quite a lot against non-extra deck focused decks. That's not to say its unwinnable but that’s what the side deck is for. We run a backrow destruction package in the form of Harpie’s feather Duster and Three copies of Cosmic Cyclone. Red Reboot also helps deal with backrow decks. The rest of the cards enable the deck to be played going first. The additional copies Barrier Statue of the Torrent and Nekroz of Valkyrus are there for the classic nekroz play of setting up a floodgate with Battle Fader style battle protection. Secret Village of the Spellcasters and Terraforming combine with any spellcaster Nekroz monster just shuts down any spell-based deck. Last but not least There can be Only One is an easy disruption card for Nekroz to play with as more often than not only one of each type of monsters will be on the field at once. Most of the Extra deck is focused around enabling Nekroz Kaleidoscope. Herald of the Ark Light and Elder Entity N’tss are commonly used for effects when ritual summoning. Everything else was chosen because they either recycle themselves or can be special summoned off of an opponent’s Monster Reborn type effects. I also tried to set these up to play around giving Lights and Fire attributes to Invocation, but several levels didn’t feature enough monsters to do this Perfectly. Nepthys, The Sacred Flame, Bahamut Shark, and Cross-Sheep are al situation tools the deck can use.

XYZ Summoning Tips- XYZ summoning Dark Rebellion XYZ Dragon isn't that hard and you only need Two Level Four Monsters the only tip I can really give you is to only summon Dark Rebellion when it is necessary for example if your opponents monster has like Four Thousand Attack Points then you definitely want to get   out Dark Rebellion and activate its effect.   Synchro Summoning Tip- If you want to get Clear Wing Synchro Dragon or Clear Wing Fast Dragon out I'd recommend to first summon Performapal Parrotrio, Performapal Spike Eagle and Performapal Stamp Turtle then once you have all the three monsters on the field use Stamp Turtle's Effect to increase Parrotrio's and Spike Eagle's by one. After that you have the required levels to Synchro Summon! Do not summon Clear Wing Synchro Dragon summon Clear Wing Fast Dragon instead since it is more useful.  Fusion Summoning Tips- Fusion Summoning with a Performapal Deck can pose a problem depending on what you draw and what's your starting hand. If you want to get out Starving Venom Fusion Dragon to try and destroy most of your opponents monsters the best way to summon Starving Venom is to Pendulum Summon Two Dark Monsters then summon Performapal Trump Witch and tribute her to add Polymerzation to your hand. For Rune-Eyes Pendulum Dragon and Beast-Eyes Pendulum Dragon I can't give any tips with them but if you want to Fusion Summon even more I'd recommend to add Two more Polymerzation's to your deck. This Deck isn't exactly meant for competitive play but you can still use it!

deck_excerpt: I explain the card choices, multiple OTKs, and more.
deck_description: I like to think of this deck as a Aggro/Combo deck. Preforms well with multiple combos and Dragoon is a easy win card. I've play tested it a lot and play this irl aswell. I hope you enjoy this deck. Main Deck Card Explanations: 1 Toon Ancient Gear Golem - Mostly used as a tribute for Special Summoning Black Luster or if u need a beatstick with piercing 3 Toon BLS - Main Boss Monster of the Toons, once per turn banish effect, can attack the turn he's summoned, 3000 ATK, always a special summon, If you can get 2 on the field you can pull off a Number 97+Number 100 OTK 2 Toon Dark Magican - Main Card used to special summon monsters or get a Toon Kingdom/Search Card 3 is too cloggy, Plenty of R7 XYZ plays with this and Red-Eyes Toon Dragon 3 Red-Eyes Toon Dragon - Used as a way to special summon big toons from hand(so TDM,TBLS,etc), if nothing to special summon after it attacks its first time I usually xyz with TDM if I can or another Red-Eyes Toon. 2 Toon Cyber Dragon - Just like a Normal Cyber Dragon, free special summon if you have no monsters and your opponent does, mostly used if a field wipe happens, otherwise I use it as a discard target for TDM effect.No Xyzs cause he is the only level 5. 3 Toon Gemini Elf - By far the best OG toon with 1900, a discard effect when she attacks directly and the level 4 helps with a lot of xyz plays. Only downside is if Kingdom is destroyed she's destroyed but she is the only card that is destroyed this way.Xyz plays with THL 2 Toon Harpie Lady - The weakest toon attack wise but she is used for her special summon to pop a spell or trap, then if you've got another THL or TGE on the field theres alot of xyz plays like the Utopia OTK or tornado dragon for another spell/trap pop, depends on the situation. 3 The Black Stone of Legend - Main Combo Starter, tributes itself for red-eyes toon dragon, then RETD effect to special summon from hand. 1 Shadow Toon - Opponent takes dmg for the attack of one of their monsters. Can really help in a pinch if you need it. TDM effect searchs any toon card so if you need it from deck to hand to finish a match that's a good way to do it. 1 Terraforming - search for toon kingdom 3 Toon Table of Contents - main search card, isnt once per turn, search for kingdom, bookmark, or page-flip based on what you already have in hand. If you got all 3 search toon terror,toon mask, or toon breifcase. 3 Toon Bookmark - Search but mostly you just want bookmark in the graveyard to protect toon kingdom. 3 Toon Page-Flip - Free Special Summon, turn one always play kingdom then page-flip for a free special summon of either TDM,TBLS, or RETD.TDM and RETD get you another special summon so in my opinion TBLS is the worst one to get when your opponent picks one randomly to summon but he is still good regardless you just don't get another special summon.Other 2 go back into deck. If playing Irl, shuffle the 3 you chose under the table, have your oppenent chose a card. 1 Double or Nothing - Used for the Utopia OTK. 2 LVL 4 into Utopia Double, Double effect, detach and add double or nothing from deck to hand, summon out utopia on top of double, he becomes a 5000 who cant attack directly, Utopia effect to stop his attack then double or nothing to give him another attack at 10000 but it has to be a monster. 1 Comic Hand - Steal an opponents monster, they become a toon, and can attack directly and are protected by toon kingdoms effect. 3 Toon Kingdom - Banish 3 from Deck isn't too bad but if you're relying on dragoon make sure it isn't either dark magician, red-eyes black dragon, or red-eyes fusion cause that bricks the entire dragoon play. Prevents targeted effects on toons and if they'd be destroyed by battle or card effects banish cards from top of deck to keep them on the field instead so if 3 would be destroyed banish 3 from top of deck. 2 Toon Briefcase - Non-targeted way to deal with a big monster that gets summoned, sends it back to deck so really good for monsters that can't be targeted and can't be destroyed by card effects. 2 Toon Mask - Free special summons if you control toon world, target a opponents monster a special summon a monster of equal or less level. 3 Toon Terror - Omni-Negate Counter trap 1 Red-Eyes Fusion - for dragoon, you either use this if you draw it turn 1 or send it to graveyard with Verte Anaconda, like I said earlier if either 3 of the cards get banished say bye to dragoon. 1 Red-Eyes Black Dragon - only used to fuse for dragoon 1 Dark Magician - I play a Red Dark Magician for style points, only used to fuse for dragoon. That's it for Main Deck Explanations on to Extra Deck. Extra Deck: Number 38:Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy - Used for the Numeron Dragon OTK or as a way to steal your opponents spells for materials and prevent attacks on weaker monsters. Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon - Cannot be destroyed by card effects and inflicts 500 every time your opponent activates a card or effect. Mecha Phantom Beast Draccosack - detach for 2 tokens, tribute 1 per turn to destroy monsters but cant attack the turn he does, if theres a token he cant be destroyed by battle or card effect. Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon - OP Broken Boss Monster Card - If you summon this say GG and shake your opponents hand. Number 11:Big Eye - Take a opponents Monster, cant attack turn it takes one. Predaplant Verte Anaconda - main way to get dragoon unless you draw red-eyes fusion, pay 2000 life points and send red-eyes fusion to graveyard to fusion summon Dragoon. a simple link 2 for a boss monster. Utopia Lighting - if utopia gets negated, go into lightning Utopia - Part of the OTK combo with double, negate and double or nothing for 10000 into a monster Utopia Double - detach, get double or nothing to hand, then special summon a utopia with double attached as material and the 1 attached to double, utopia gains 2500 with double as material but can attack directly Time Thief Redoer - can distrupt opponents plays Tornado Dragon - pop spells/traps Number 101: Silent Honor Ark - detach 2 to steal a monster as material for this card Evilswarm Excition Knight - Field Wipe if opponent has more cards Number 97 - detach to summon Numeron Dragon with Number 38 as material on Numeron Number 100:Numeron Dragon - detach to gain attack, with number 97 out he becomes a 9000 atk but with number 97 the effect locks you into attacking with numeron Side Deck If you wanna play pure toons add pot of extravagance in for the dragoon cards and switch out dragoon and anaconda for another red-eyes flare metal dragon and blackship of corn. There is to many combos to go into but I hope you learned some plays from the explanations. Main play is 2 monsters on the field for verte anaconda to get dragoon turn one.Thanks for reading :)

deck_excerpt: An infinite-negate rogue deck, that can achieve even more. Strengths: Consistency, First-Turn Lockdown, and the ability to power thru at least 3 negat
deck_description: A budget, OG-Style, for-fun rogue deck with lots of pitching and a single go-first strat - but diverse and powerful enough that going second you can power through many boards. For those of you unfamiliar, objective A will be to get out Simorgh using Reprodocus and anything; and then get out union carrier to attach a thunderbird to it. For the main big bad combo: Get out simorgh with one-two cards using either crusadia (50/50 chance to extend into full board), or beast/gates, or any number of other cheeky and easy ways (gold sarc, AOD hawk/roar). Then you want to, if possible, go into elpy. For this you can use: Brotaur Draco (you will always have this available if you do maximus play) Wyverbuster (searchable) Collapserpent (searchable) Or chaos space to search for one, giving you 7/40 chance of having one as your first card drawn, getting one off a draw, etc. Once you get to this stage you have a few options. A: if Chaos creator is in hand, you can make Trish, use trish + some ss'd-off-the-banish material to make carrier. Then use creator to bring back whatever you banished from YOUR OPPONENTS EXTRA DECK (or your own if theirs is really that terrible). You could get friggin toad. ABC. W/e they have that you like. With one more SS you can even make I:P masq. B: if chaos creator is NOT in hand, you can do the whole elpy->brotaur->red-eyes shabang and banish elpy for the summon, make carrier off of these mats. You will have one material left for pisty if you choose to extend. If  you can access one more dragon (outside pisty eff), you can easily make trish off of a pisty extender - and therefor make I:P masq, and a next-round apoll. C: You got no dragons for the big combo? Big oof. Don't worry, you can probably still make the infinite-negate combo, at least, and maybe at least a Bagooska or No. 38. Red-eyes errata may hurt, but you CAN instead search out Lightpulsar (very uncommonly) to get some decent good recursion. If you decide to use curious, which I don't recommend, you can plug it in to your GY for your elpy<->pisty combos. The one thing you do NOT want to do is lose simorgh before your end phase - but if you ABSOLUTELY must, you can probably clean board with Almarduke. Best of all: if your opponent tried to nibiru you here, they'll be screwed over. Also, if you rich guys have Nibiru, run a copy of that instead of raigeki in your side.

deck_excerpt: Just a fun water based deck I made!!!!!!!!!
deck_description: Just a fun water based deck I made!!!!!!!!!

DISCLAIMER: THIS DECK IS NOT META AND ITS MEANT TO TEST THE CEILING OF THIS ARCHETYPE. IT WILL LOSE TO A WELL TIMED HAND TRAP!

So the deck is not linear (as the card advantage all come from drawing cards) besides the opening play of trying to make Halc (which is either rescue cat or figure someway to dump a tuner and another monster from your opening hand onto the field) for Deskbot 1 to Auroradon to Warbluran.

From there, plays branch out depending on remaining hand but usually, use the warbluran to tribute a token to become lvl 2 and synchro away into librarian. your field should be TG librarian and Deskbot 1.

Now from there, synchro climb your way with Librarian draws and adapt to what you draw with ragin, stardust warrior, Ravenous crocodragon. Use your extra deck monster zone for monsters you know you wont keep on field to keep your main monster zone as free as possible. the easiest way to make Cosmic Blazar Dragon (or Quasar if you like it better) is actually with a Librarian, Unicore and Marshall Metal Marcher (tho Librarian, Ragin and formula also works ofc)

Your best main deck fabled is Grimro (duh) and Krus (after you have a full GY so it functions as any fabled and also revive unicore in the end after being used as material)

Dont be afraid to pot of avarice away less optimal creatures as sometimes its neccessary (but usually you would target extra deck monster besides auroradon because thats for Borreload savage dragon, and the next best targets are Grimro and Krus to hopefully draw them again)

The new Tuner Alfac is similar to Kushano except its a hard once per turn but special summon itself and banish like Ganesha. So with Ganesha its an easy ragin synchro. these two are usually what I get with rescue cat to link into Halc in the beginning

The Field spell is decent as it dumps kushano (or Alfac) and an extra discard outlet but otherwise its just an extra search target for the other New card, Marchosia (that special itself like Chawa, or be discarded to search the field or trap. both Hard once per turn effects). I am testing the trap card as another search target but probably will cut it.

everything else is trial and error. again, the deck is not linear because its super reliant on draw (and fixing the hand with grimro after the draws) so it requires a lot of thinking in trying to reach the synchros. but it is very fun to play!

PS. it is very satisfying to use Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon to run over a Red-Eyes Dragoon, you should try it!

deck_excerpt: One of my favorite decks and Arch-types. It is also has a fun gimmick to it.
deck_description: Okay so too jet stream this Fire Kings like being destroyed to use their effects. Main goal is use that Gimmicks to your advantage. Secondly all "Fire King" monster share this effect "If a face-up "Fire King" monster you control is destroyed by a card effect (except during the Damage Step): You can Special Summon this card from your hand." called the "Fire King Summon". There are two exceptions without this ability Fire King Avatar Arvata and Fire King High Avatar Garunix. Thirdly they all have a floating effect upon their destruction. This Deck has four Boss monsters plus a few option in the Side Deck Boss Monsters Fire King High Avatar Garunix likes being destroyed by card effect to only resurrect himself on the NEXT Standby Phase and destroy all other monsters on the Field indiscriminately. However, if he is destroyed by battle he can bring out a different "Fire King" monster from your Deck to the Field. Arvata would be a good choice because of his resurrection ability. Works well with another copy of himself and Sacred Phoenix. This will clear the Field at the start of each turn. Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys is much like High Garunix but destroy card in the Spell and Trap card zones. Cataclysmic Scorching Sunburner is basically a 2600, 8 started beat stick. Easy to get out because he can summon himself when one of your fire-type monster(s) is destroyed either by battle or card effect. Then deal half the ATK of one of the FIRE monsters that was sent to the Graveyard. Bonfire Colossus is another 2600, 8 started beat stick, and easy to get out and can trigger any "Fire King" monster's effect. Summons himself by destroying two of FIRE monsters that you control on the Field. Other Monsters Fire King Avatar Arvata one of the "Black Sheep" of the "Fire King" family that doesn't do the "Fire King Summon". However, he has his own fun an unique ability. Being a Spell Speed 2 quick effect to negate the effect of a monster upon its activation. At the coast of destroying one FIRE monster from either the Hand or Field. Upon his own destruction by any matter, you can Special Summon one FIRE Beast, Beast-Warrior, or Winged Beast monster from your Graveyard, except himself. The catch is the it has its effects negated, and is also destroyed during the End Phase. NOTE: Both of his effects are once per a turn. However this is a good way to bring back a High Garunix that has been beaten in battle, or bring him out from your Hand with the 1st effect. Fire King Avatar Barong after his defeat by card effect he sends a postcard to another "Fire King" monster in the Deck and during the NEXT Standby Phase the "Fire King" monster whom received the postcard is brought to the Hand. this is a good way to search for "Fire King" monsters in particular High Garunix, Arvata, or Yaksha. Fire King Avatar Garunix can bring any "Fire King Avatar" monster from your Deck to the Field. However, Garunix must be die by your opponent's card effect or in a fight. NOTE: Arvata, or Yaksha are great targets for this effect. Fire King Avatar Kirin brings another FIRE monster from the Deck with itself to the Graveyard when he goes in any matter. High Garunix or Sacred Phoenix are okay targets for this effect to set up a combo with Arvata or the Spell cards Onslaught of the Fire Kings or Circle of the Fire Kings. Fire King Avatar Yaksha destroys one card in your Hand or your Field upon his destructions in any matter. This is really good to be able to active any "Fire King" monster's effects from the hand. Flamvell Firedog when he defeats an opponents monster by battle you can bring any FIRE monster from your Deck to the Field with 200 DEF or less except another copy of himself. Yaksha, Barong, Flame Tiger, or Cataclysmic Scorching Sunburner. Flame Ruler counts as two tributes for a FIRE monster. Ultimate Baseball Kid gains 1000 ATK for each FIRE monster on the Field except for himself, and can send one FIRE monster you control to inflict 500 damage to your opponent. Little Chimera is an ATK booster for FIRE monsters and ATK bane to WATER monsters. Raging Flame Sprite is a good card all around. Fencing Fire Ferret drags down another face up monster your opponents controls with it and inflicts 500 damage to your opponent at the same time. Flame Tiger is just a 1800, 4 star beat stick. With a decent effect. Spell Cards Fire King Island well is a ticking time bomb. By that when it goes boom all your monsters on your Field go boom with it. However your "Fire Kings" will like that. Plus the bonus effects. 1st effect "During your Main Phase: You can destroy 1 monster in your hand or you control, and if you do, add 1 "Fire King" monster from your Deck to your hand." NOTE: It can activate "Fire King" effects from the hand plus searches for another "Fire King". It's 2nd allows you to Special Summon 1 FIRE Winged Beast-Type monster from your hand when you have no monsters on the Field. NOTE: You can only use one of these effects per a turn. Circle of the Fire Kings allows you to basically swap one FIRE monsters for another. In other words swapping one of your FIRE monsters for a defeated High Garunix back from the beyond. Onslaught of the Fire Kings brings out one FIRE Beast, Beast-Warrior, or Winged Beast monster from your Deck when you don't have any monsters on the Field. However, at the coast of its effect and it being destroyed at the End Phase. Wink Wink "Fire Kings" like that. Especially Hight Garunix. Burden of the Mighty because this deck lacks ATK power using Burden of the Mighty to even the playing Field. Trap Cards Backfire does what its name suggest. When your FIRE monsters are destroyed by any means deals 500 damage to your opponent. Kickfire is like Backfire but with counters and your monsters need to be destroyed by card effect. then you can deal 1000 damage to your opponent. NOTE: "Fire Kings" like being destroyed. Phoenix Wing Wind Blast is nothing overly special just discard a card and place an opponents card on top of their deck. Regretful Rebirth if High Garunix is beaten in battle you can bring him back with this card and use its effect at the same time. Horn of the Phantom Beast is an ATK booster for Beast and Beast-Warrior monsters, also gives a +1 hand advantage upon defeating an opponents monster. Extra Deck and Side Deck Are added mostly because they look cool. They are useable but its not recommended. While the Side Deck give option of Boss Monsters that synergize well with FIRE monsters to Swap out Bonfire Colossus, Cataclysmic Scorching Sunburner, Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys if you want. Well Hope you enjoyed and Good Luck and have Fun.

deck_excerpt: Melffy Tribrigade post BLVO. Using Melffy and rescue rabbits to generate advantages and tribrigade to break apart boards.
deck_description: Use Tribrigade to set up negates and push for games and melffy to enable follow up in the future turns.   Fraktall/Tenki Look for access to Tri-brigade Fraktall, Fracktall -> Kit -> Nervall  enable you to add Fraktall/Kerass with 3 bodies in grave. Add Fraktall if you don't have/want to extend, since the 1900 ATK will allow it to survive to the next turn easier compared to Kerass. Add Kerass for extending plays beyond Rescue Rabbit and later plays, or combining with with a kalantosa in hand. They will enable you to banish the 3 bodies to summon Simorgh, Bird of Divinity and at end phase summon Mist Valley Apex Avian for a negate.   Catty and Puppy(or Puppy) If you have Catty and Puppy in hand, there are 2 lines of plays. Use Puppy to summon Kalantosa to destroy 1 card, and Catty to search Hop Ear Squadron. Hop Ear Squadron target Kalantosa, summon Herald. While Herald is a negate, it also banishes monster from the deck and hand sent to GY. This will sometime force decks to enter the battle phase to eliminate Herald before continuing combos. Alternatively, search Rescue Rabbit or Kerass for plays next turn or  Alpha, the Master of Beasts, to out threats.   Rescue Rabbit: Puppy Catty: Tribute Rabbit, summon Puppy, Catty, overlay into Excited Melffy Tribrigade: Tribute Rabbit, Summon Puppt/Catty and Tribrigade Kit. Overlay for Melffy of the Forest, detach Kit, mill Nervall and add Kerass. Summon Kerass, Banish 3 for Simorgh, Bird of divinity. You can also banish 4 for Tri-Brigade Shuraig the Ominous Omen if you plan to use Puppy to trigger its banish effects.   Nervall/Kit+Beast/Winged Beast/Beast-warrior: Summon Nervall/Kit ->Almiraj (Kit mils Nervall) Add Kerass, Pitch fodder, Summon Kerass Kerass banish 2, summon Raidraptor Wise Strix Almiraj effect, target Kerass/Wise Strix Wise Strix +Kerass ->Simorgh, Bird of Divinity   Ending Games: -Use Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom to summon tribrigade/rescue rabbit locked in hand for additional bodies or Kalantosa to pop a card. -Use Tri-Brigade Rugal the Silver Sheller to summon monster after the battle phase to return it to your hand. -Don't be afraid to link Tri-Brigade Shuraig the Ominous Omen for other monster like Accesscode Talker or Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom. -Omen can search cards like Rescue Rabbits to extend. -Sandayu summons a large token and is a extra beast body when sent to the grave. -Use Acesscode Talker to chain block effects of Tribrigade links. -Alpha, the Master of Beasts can target monster other than himself, you can bounce several cards at once. -Consider holding back on Fraktall's second effect if you have enough bodies in grave, or use it after you summon Fraktall and use Fraktall's effect summon a body.   Where is Obedience School? Obedience Schooled locks you into beast, and the end board for that consist of Excited Melffy and Melffy of the Forest. While powerful at times, generating pops,negates and followups, all requires Excited Melffy to resolve and your opponent to summon a monster. This is a issue since effects that activates on summon cannot be negated until you commit to a herald, which is the last interaction you have. Compared to Mist Valley Apex Avian, Avian can negate cards at any time in the combo and cannot be targeted while dodging Nibiru. Additionally, the beast lock makes it difficult to break boards going second, taking away access to Access code Talker that pops 1-2 cards, or Omen, who banish without targetting.   Where is Nealogia AA-Zeus? It is a consideration when you lack enough reach to kill your opponent. I prefer passing on Omen for a banish and a chance to grab cards like Rescue Rabbits and Alpha compare to a board nuke. Please let me know if you feel like its good enough to run!   Why the Triple Tactical Talent? The deck should have enough handtraps and setup to survive going first, and the Triple Tactical Talent enable you to get information for optimal disruption or get some help breaking tough boards. Do keep in mind about the restriction on tribrigades's link material when stealing monsters.   D.D. Crow? Its a winged beast handtrap that can be banished for Tri-Brigade. While not quite the format staple it was, many decks still rely on the GY to generate or recur resources.   Infinite Negates/Floodgates? Barrier Statue is powerful, but its stats are weak. While we want to survive to the next turn, we cannot let the opponent build up boards with several negates since breaking those boards requires drawing above average hands. Apex Avian and Thunderbird loop is powerful, but add additional bricks to the deck that is doesn't want to draw several of its cards. While you don't want to draw cards like Kalantosa,Nervall, or Kit, they can still help in breaking boards or starting combos. For example, Kalantosa can be used with Ferrijit the Barren Blossom to destroy cards, or overlayed with Kerass to summon Excited Melffy but drawing it alone is terrible. Nervall and Kit can start combos, but require other specific cards.   Can I run one Kalantosa? I wouldn't recommend it since having a second one in deck allow you to use it with Excited Melffy and Puppy in one turn.

deck_excerpt: Less brick cus Wise Strix > Force Strix turbo. Means we dont even use Zephyros while ending with the same Bardiche+Redoer(trap mat)+Dark Requiem(3 mat
deck_description: After billions of testing, I found that going Force Strix before Wise Strix eats more resource/needs more brick than going to Wise Strix directly. So, we cut all the generic r4nk engines, the only lv4 we need are the Raidraptor ones. I will explain the cards role first, before the combo. Starters: 3 Tribute Lanius (+1 sending Mimicry), 3 Mimicry (+1), and Raiders Wing (+1 but have to start with Force Strix, it means dead if drawn with Strangle Lanius, best as combo piece). Extenders: 3 Vanishing, 3 Pain Lanius (it can become lv4), 2 Strangle Lanius (we need 2 as combo pieces) and Singing Lanius (dead if drawn with Strangle Lanius). The non-lv4: Heel Eagle, Danger Thunderbird (possible +1 but can miss), and Caligo Claw Crow. The PKs: 2 Silent Boots (to guarantee Bardiche effect, can play 1 tho), and 2 RUM Force, Shade Brigandine (combo piece, can be extender but Redoer will lose its disruption), Fog Blade (extra disruption if we draw either the RUM/Shade Brigandine). The combo is Wise Strix+lv4, but gotta be careful to use the combo pieces cus all of them is once per turn. If we didn't open the starter, it means we have to put 3 Dark Winged-Beast (1 of them is lv4) on field. Wise Strix will summon Mimicry/Raiders Wing (depends on which one we havent used), overlay it with other lv4 we have to Force Strix, use Force add Strangle/Singing Lanius (ss it), use Wise set RUM Force, use Mimicry/Raiders Wing in GY (Mimicry can add Nest/Pain/Strangle), ss the extender, make Rusty Bardiche with Force+Wise Strix, use Bardiche send Boots set Shade Brigandine, ss Shade Brigandine on Bardiche link marker, make Force again with Strangle/Singing + the extender, use Force add another Strangle, use RUM Force banish 3 (dont banish our +1 or Heel Eagle) ss Arsenal Falcon, use Arsenal (dont detach Force) ss Vanishing, use Vanishing ss Strangle from hand, use Strangle ss lv4 from GY, make Redoer with Shade Brigandine on Bardiche link marker, use Bardiche destroy Arsenal, use Arsenal ss Ultimate Falcon, make Dark Rebellion with the remaining lv4 on Bardiche link marker, use Boots GY eff add RUM Force, set it. On the opponent's main phase, we can use RUM Force to trigger Bardiche while summoning 3 mats Dark Requiem. Pay attention to the combo cus using Strangle effect as starter play kills the full combo (das why its only 2 copies, not 3 ofs despite being generic dark extender). Against Mekk-Knighy/zone reliant deck, we gotta place the Nest/RUM/Fogblade on the free zone or with Ultimate Falcon cus it is immune. We're using D.D. Crow as handtrap cus it's useful in combo while being not too bad against meta (Dogma: Titaniklad/Shaddoll monster, Halq: Martial Metal target/001/Plaguespreader, dino: Miscellaneousarus, Eld: anything, Zoo: Ramram), but bad against Dragoon/Zexal running rampant in TCG. Pros: Super consistent legit board with follow-up (Nest/Raiders Wing). Cons: 2 cards combo (3 if we dont open the +1).

deck_excerpt: A simple Dragon Link deck that focuses on bringing out Borrelend Dragon.
deck_description: This is a simple Dragon Link deck where the combo should end with a board of Borrelend Dragon and a Borreload Savage Dragon. There are three main ways to begin: Black Metal Dragon, Starliege Seyfert or Chaos Space.  If you start first, summon Black Metal Dragon. Now, this can be accomplished by Normal Summoning it from the hand but you can also Special Summon it from the deck with One For One. Then Link it for Striker Dragon to get Boot Sector Launch and Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon. Banish Striker Dragon to Special Summon RED MD and then use its effect to Special Summon Black Metal Dragon from the graveyard. Then use them to link summon Romulus. Grab Dragon Ravine. Activate Ravine and discard a card to send Absorouter from the deck to the Graveyard. Though, if you have Absorouter in your hand, discard it and then send Brotaur from the deck to the grave. Next, grab Rokket Tracer and add it to the hand. Replace Ravine with Boot Sector Launch and then Special Summon Rokket Tracer. Now, destroy Boot Sector and special summon a Level 4 Rokket from your deck. Then you use Rokket Tracer to Link Summon Pisty then use Romulus and your other Rokket to Link Summon Quadborrel. Then use Pisty to special summon from your Graveyard or Special Summon one of your banished dragons. Link then both for Dillingerous Dragon. Now, activated Quadborrel to discard a card and destroy Dillingerous. This special summons Tracer, your Level 4 Rokket and Dillingerous Back. Now, use Quadborrel, Dillingerous and one of your Rokkets to Link Summon Borrelend Dragon. Then, use Borrelend's effect to target your remaining Rokket so you can special summon the other Rokket from the Graveyard. Then synchro summon for Borreload Savage Dragon. Equip it with Romulus. Now, you have two negates you can use and better if you have more negates available in hand.  You can figure out how to use Chaos Space and Starliege Seyfert.

Now, this can be accomplished by Normal Summoning it from the hand but you can also Special Summon it from the deck with One For One. Then Link it for Striker Dragon to get Boot Sector Launch and Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon. Banish Striker Dragon to Special Summon RED MD and then use its effect to Special Summon Black Metal Dragon from the graveyard. Then use them to link summon Romulus. Grab Dragon Ravine. Activate Ravine and discard a card to send Absorouter from the deck to the Graveyard. Though, if you have Absorouter in your hand, discard it and then send Brotaur from the deck to the grave. Next, grab Rokket Tracer and add it to the hand. Replace Ravine with Boot Sector Launch and then Special Summon Rokket Tracer. Now, destroy Boot Sector and special summon a Level 4 Rokket from your deck. Then you use Rokket Tracer to Link Summon Pisty then use Romulus and your other Rokket to Link Summon Quadborrel. Then use Pisty to special summon from your Graveyard or Special Summon one of your banished dragons. Link then both for Dillingerous Dragon. Now, activated Quadborrel to discard a card and destroy Dillingerous. This special summons Tracer, your Level 4 Rokket and Dillingerous Back. Now, use Quadborrel, Dillingerous and one of your Rokkets to Link Summon Borrelend Dragon. Then, use Borrelend's effect to target your remaining Rokket so you can special summon the other Rokket from the Graveyard. Then synchro summon for Borreload Savage Dragon. Equip it with Romulus. Now, you have two negates you can use and better if you have more negates available in hand.  You can figure out how to use Chaos Space and Starliege Seyfert.
Say NO to you opponent

deck_excerpt: This is TeamSamuraiX1's Deck Profile of Phantom Knights
deck_description:
This deck was originally created by TeamSamuraiX1 in his video of Phantom Knights Deck Profile. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KD2XI08GQO4&t=903s The video will explain all the reasons why he chooses these cards. Here I will list the many combos you can do with this deck as well as the cards. Acronyms and meanings: ATK = Attack OTK = One Turn Kill GY = Graveyard PK = Phantom Knights EMZ = Extra Monster Zone BZ = Banish Zone MZ = Monster Zone STZ = Spell and Trap Zone Combo 1: Torn Scales + 1 Discard
  1. Open with Torn Scales and a discard (of any kind).
  2. Normal summon Torn Scales, activate its effect to discard 1 card in your hand to your GY, then send 1 Ancient Cloak to the grave.
  3. Banish Ancient Cloak from your GY to search for Silent Boots.
  4. Use Silent Boots effect to special summon itself from your hand to the field.
  5. Link both Torn Scales and Silent Boots to the GY to link summon Cherubini to the EMZ.
  6. Use Cherubini's effect to send Graff from the deck to the GY.
  7. Graff's effect activates from the GY, special summons Cir from the deck to the field.
  8. Banish Silent Boots to search for Fog Blade.
  9. Activate Torn Scales' effect to special summon itself from your GY to your field
  10. Xyz summon Leviair over Cir and Torn scales.
  11. Use Leviairs' effect to discard Cir (Xyz material) to special Ancient Cloak from your BZ to your field in ATK position.
  12. Cir's effect activates from the GY to special summon Graff from the GY to the field (or MZ).
  13. Link away Graff and Cherubini to link summon Rusty Bardiche to the EMZ. 
  14. Activate Rusty Bardiche's effect to send Ragged Gloves to the GY and set 1 Fog Blade from your deck to you SPZ.
  15. Set the other fog blade.
  16. Activate Ancient Cloak's effect to target Rusty Bardiche, it gains 800 ATK and changes Ancient Cloak to defense position.
  17. Link away Ancient Cloak and Leviair to the GY to link summon Verte Anaconda to the down left link arrow that Rusty Bardiche is pointing at (3rd MZ).
  18. Activate its effect to pay 2000 LP and send Red-Eyes Fusion to the GY, it becomes that spell cards effect and sends 1 Red-Eyes Black Dragon and Dark Magician to the GY to fusion summon Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon to left of Verte Anaconda (2nd MZ).
This combo not only allows you to set up for an OTK for the following turn but also gives you many negates/protection that comes in the form of Dark Dragoon and the 2 Fog blades. Along with the 3 combo extenders in the GY for your next turn (Ancient Cloak, Torn Scales, and Ragged Gloves). Combo 1: Torn Scales + Any PK Monster
  1. Have Torn Scales and any PK monster in your hand (in this case Ragged Gloves).
  2. Normal summon Torn Scales, activate its effect to discard Ragged Gloves to the GY, and send Ancient Cloak to the GY.
  3. Activate Ancient Cloak's effect to banish itself and search for Silent Boots.
  4. Activate Silent Boots effect to special summon itself from your hand to the field.
  5. Link away to link summon Cherubini to the left EMZ.
  6. Activate Cherubini and send Graff from the deck to GY.
  7. Activate Graff to special summon Cir from the deck to the field.
  8. Activate Silent Boots to banish itself from the GY to add PK's Rank-Up-Magic Force to your hand.
  9. Torn Scales effect activates and special summons itself from the GY to the field.
  10. Overlay both monster to Xyz summon Leviair on the left side of Cherubini in ATK position (1st MZ)
  11. Activate Leviair's effect by detaching Cir to the GY and special Ancient Cloak from the BZ to the field in ATK position.
  12. Activate Cir's effect to special summon Graff from the GY to the field.
  13. Link summon Rusty Bardiche by sending Cherubini and Graff to the GY and place it in the same EMZ.
  14. Activate Rusty Bardiche, send Stained Greaves from deck to GY, and set 1 Fog Blade from your deck to the SPZ.
  15. Activate Ragged Gloves by banishing it from the GY and send 1 Wings from the Deck to the GY.
  16. Activate Stained Greaves, banish Wings to special summon it onto the field in ATK position.
  17. Xyz summon Beak Sword to the 3rd MZ where the bottom right link arrow points to from Rusty Bardiche.
  18. Bardiche effect activates and destroys Break Sword.
  19. Break Sword GY effect activates and special summons Stained Greaves and Ancient Cloak in ATK position.
  20. Xyz summon Dark Rebellion Xyz Dragon in the same place as the previous Xyz monster.
  21. Set PK's Rank-Up-Magic Force in your SPZ and end your turn.
  22. During your opponent's turn, after they summon a monster, activate the Rank-Up spell, banish Graff from the GY to the BZ and Xyz summon on top of Dark Rebellion Xyz Dragon with Dark Reqieum Xyz Dragon.
  23. Rusty Bardiche effect activates to target and destroys a card on the field.
After completing the combo your board should look like this:
  • 1 Leviair on the 1st MZ
  • 1 Rusty Bardiche in the EMZ above the 2nd MZ
  • 1 Fog Blade beneath Rusty Bardiche in the STZ
  • and 1 Dark Reqieum Xyz Dragon on the 3rd MZ.
When completed, you have 5 disruptions. 1 from Rusty Bardiche (instantly used after the combo ends), 3 saved up monster negates from Dark Reqieum, and a Fog Blade.

deck_excerpt: Dogmatika Invoked, the most powerful control deck of the format.
deck_description:
This is a standard Dogmatika Invoked deck. All cards are legal as of 11/4/2020.   Strategy: Your strategy going first should be to turbo out Shaddoll Schism (in order to summon El Shaddoll Winda on your opponents turn) by sending El Shaddoll Apkallone and Titaniklad the Ash Dragon to the graveyard using Dogmatika Maximus's effect. For longer matches you can repeatedly send Elder Entity N'tss and PSY-Framelord Omega to the graveyard using Dogmatika Maximus's effect to pop one of your opponent's cards and then recycle your resources back to the extra deck. You can stop your opponent's plays using the powerful and searchable trap card Dogmatika Punishment. When you have a clear board, an OTK can be performed by using Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted's effect to boost your Dogmatika cards attack power. You can also use Invoked Augoeides's effect to banish a fusion monster from the graveyard to gain a temporary attack boost.   Card Choice: Both handtraps Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Effect Veiler can be link summoned into Salamangreat Almiraj and then Secure Gardna; doing so puts an extra deck monster on the field immediately allowing you to special summon any of the Dogmatika cards from your hand. This makes Effect Veiler arguably more valuable over the other popular handtrap PSY-Framegear Gamma. We run two of Dogmatika Maximus and Dogmatika Fleurdelis as a precaution against banishing them when we activate Pot of Desires. Given the popularity of powerful extra deck monsters such as Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon we play several outs to hard-to-get-rid-of monsters:
  • Forbidden Droplet
  • Ice Dragon's Prison
  • Triple Tactics Talent
  Strengths: The deck is very consistent. You can start your plays using just one card such as Nadir Servant or Magical Meltdown. There is a lot of room for hand traps or other going second cards depending on the match-up. Your turn one board is very threatening. You can end on a powerful floodgate and multiple negates (Invoked Mechaba, El Shaddoll Winda, Dogmatika Fleurdelis)   Weaknesses: This deck works works best if you're familiar with your opponent's strategy. You can easily lose advantage if you destroy or negate the wrong cards during your opponent's combo play. Dogmatika effects can lock you out of the extra deck for a turn. Be mindful of when you cannot summon invoked fusion monsters. This deck suffers if you cannot resolve Dogmatika Maximus because your opponent does not play extra deck monsters. Your opponent can potentially counter Dogmatika Maximus with cards such as Cyber Dragon Nova or Elder Entity N'tss. This deck is reliant on searching cards from the deck and sending cards to the graveyard and is therefore susceptible to hand traps such as Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Dimension Shifter.

deck_excerpt: 60 card Ghostricks with a Subterror (sorta) engine
deck_description: Got the idea for this from a deck I saw on a Table 500 replay, although I don't know who originally made it. Shame. Anyway, I decided to build my own version of the deck in my futile attempts to make Ghostrick work, because I love Ghostrick. Note that this deck is really more so an expierement, so any suggestions are appreciated.  Deck guide. 1x Mummy- Great extra normal summon, but locks you into dark monsters, which conflicts with the subterrors. I decided to run at 1 to avoid the xenophobia of it. 3x Skeleton- Banishes cards from the top of your opponent's deck, can be a huge mill if you've set up a board 2x Jiangshi- Easy searcher, although it's quite slow 1x Yeti- serves to stall out and protect your weak boss monsters 3x Witch- just easy book of moon on legs 2x Yuki-Onna- pretty slow but still another book of moon on legs 3x Fairy- Book of Moon and monster recovery, fantastic for the archetype 2x Nekomusume- Another Book of Moon on legs... i think im seeing a pattern here 3x Doll- Book of Eclipse on legs, and a nice special summon to set up for more plays 2x Jackfrost- Negates an attack and another book of moon on legs, also special summons himself for later 2x Mary- Easy special summons, helps to get out the XYZ 3x Ultramafus- Easy special summon and interacts well with the ghostricks flipping themselves3 3x Speleogeist- book of moon and cripples and opponent's boss monster, also see above 2x Stalagmo- Nice draw and GY setup, also easy special summon with the ghostricks 2x Umastryx- Easy monster removal and special summons itself with the ghostricks 3x Guru- Reuses flip effects, it's also part of a lock but I forget what the lock is tbh 3x Archer- shuffles monsters into the deck if they're face down, interacts really well with cards like Book of Moon and a lot of the Ghostrick's effects 3x Fiendess- Nice special summon and negate 3x Clash-  Nice stat boost, reuses cards 3x Hidden City- Negates attacks and reuses flip effects 3x Book of Moon- helps the deck as this is Book of Moon: the deck, so 2x Go-Round- Another book of moon that reuses flip monsters 3x Break- nice special summon that can go into an XYZ 3x Succesion- searches flip monsters and such, good card 2x Angel of Mischief- Boss monster lol 2x Alucard- removes set cards to fuck over decks like Altergiest, nice monster to rank up in to Angel 2x Socuteboss- Monster removal and basically eradicates a monster zone 2x Dullahan- Cripples a monster, making it easier to run over 2x Behemoth Fiendess- Nice special summon and GY setup Playing guide It's not super complex. Get out your Ghostricks and use their effects to flip them face down, then special summon some of the behemoths. Afterwards, flip them back up with one of the other card effects and overlay them into an XYZ, rank up that XYZ into a Mischief. Protect Mischief and try to get her to 10 if you want, as you go in for an OTK with the strong behemoths. Any suggestions are highly appreciated, as again, this is more of a test than anything. Have a godo day
