deck_excerpt: Ghostrick Mystic Mine stall for an alternate win con
deck_description: So. A Ghostrick deck dedicated to Angel of Mischief's alternate win con, by stalling and drawing to get her to 10. It's quite horrible and degenerate and I love it. And yes, I hate myself too; don't go and whine in the comments about "degeneracy", this is just a deck I made for shits and giggles man. Just run Cosmic Cyclone if you hate Mystic Mine that much. Anyways, deck guide. 3x Mummy- Much more usable than the last deck, since this deck only runs dark monsters. Fantastic extra normal summon 3x Skeleton- hee hee, deck mill/banish go brrr 2x Jiangshi- slow ass searcher, but it's the best you're getting in Ghostricks 1x Yeti- helps stall and protect Angel 3x Witch- Book of moon on legs, helps slow the opponent 2x Yuki-onna- also  book of moon on legs 3x Fairy- Book of Eclipse and monster recovery in one 3x Doll- Book of Eclipse on legs, also special summons and easy monster 2x Jackfrost- Basically attack negation if your mystic mine is dead or if you didnt open one 2x Lantern- see above 3x Mary- easy special summon 3x Ragged Gloves- part of the Phantom Knights engine, buffs and searches 3x Anchient Cloak- Searches, part of the Phantom Knights engine 3x Silent Boots- Easy special summon for an XYZ, part of the engine 3x Mystic Mine- Centerpiece of the deck, stalls out the opponent to get Angel to 10 1x Terraforming- Searches Mystic 1x Metaverse- Also searches/activates Mystic 3x Extragance- Easy draw, 3 of all the XYZ and such so there's not much risk 3x Angel- Get it to 10 lol 3x Alucard- removes set cards for stuff like Altergiest, also ranks up into Angel 3x Socuteboss- Monster removal, rank up into Angel 3x Dullahan- Cripples a monster and ranks up into Angel 1x Linkuribo- Banish lol 1x Unicorn- banish lol 1x Pheonix- banish lol Playing guide This deck, like my other Ghostrick one, is quite simple. Activate Mystic Mine or search it to stall out as long as possible. Use your Ghostricks to either; get enough out to make an XYZ, or set one and pass, as your opponent will most likely be unable to kill it due to Mystic Mine. Afterwards, Flip summon and normal summon, etc etc, and XYZ into Angel. From there, just stall and draw to get her to 10, and watch as everyone at your locals and play group shuns you. Any suggestions are appreciated because this deck is top tier shit. Have a good day.

deck_excerpt: I got bored of Linkross combos, so I came over here and posted this
deck_description:
So this is one of my favorite decks. I really like Tarotrei, so I wanted to make a deck around her. And what do you know? 2 of the best flip monsters (Deus and Pot) are both level 9 and possess types and attributes that are different than Tarotrei's making them Monstrosity targets. I see this deck as a culmination of the best flip strategies available (similar to how PePe was in its prime, making use of the best pendulums available). The only thing I think I missed that deserved a chance was Shaddolls, but they don't have the position interaction of Subterrors, their levels are too small, and let's be honest, when was the last time you saw a Shaddoll player set and pass? They only do it if they have to or if the monster was summoned face-down, but most of the time they will be using the Shaddoll's monsters 2nd effect. Besides, u don't remember Shaddolls for their flip effects, do u? U remember Construct. And Winda. Fusion monsters. Sometimes summoned during your turn. Oh yeah, FLIP effects are treated as mandatory effects. So even if the effect is optional, you will never miss timing with FLIP effects. Putting that aside, let's get into the ratios:   Monsters Nibiru: Great hand trap, searchable off gallant granite, and can be used to pay the full cost of a ritual. It also helps when going second. Deus X-Krawler: His first effect doesn't matter much, as you'll most likely flip him urself by the time he's summoned. His floating effect isn't a big deal either, but it can search Tarotrei. The main effect we want is the floodgate. After being flipped, it doesn't let ur opponent activate monster effects on the field. Continuous effects, as well as monster effects off the field, will not be negated. His other purposes are being a Monstrosity target and a big ritual material. Pot of the Forbidden: Lvl 9, so he's a Monstrosity target. He also makes for an easy ritual summon. When he is flipped, he gives u access to 1 of 4 effects: Pot of Greed, Giant Trunade, Raigeki, or the Forceful Sentry. That's right: all of those effects are on normal spell cards, 3 of which are banned, and the last of which is limited. Subterror Behemoth Voltelluric: Our first Subterror. Same w/  Deus and Pot, he makes an easy ritual and is a target for Monstrosity. Upon being flipped, he can take control of an opponent's set monster until the end of your next turn. This may sound situational, but between Tarotrei and Subterror Guru, you'll be flipping ur opponent's monsters left and right. Another big thing to note: since you can flip ur monsters during your opponent's turn, you can use take a monster they control during their turn, and keep it until the end of ur turn. Unlike Mind Control, u have no restrictions on what u an do w/ the monster. Subterror Guru: When he's flipped, he searches a Subterror card. Then, you can flip another monster on the field along w/ him face-down, becoming a Spell Speed 2 effect if u control another face-up Subterror card. Note that flipping, for example, Subterror Final Battle during ur opponent's turn will allow you to use Guru's second effect as if it was a quick effect, but only during that chain (unless you had a different face-up Subterror card, of course). Deskbot 003: So ritual-focused decks have this problem: they are not naturally consistent. Thankfully, we have been give loads of Ritual support over the years. I could have had Manju here, and don't get me wrong I am considering using him. But why use Manju and search half of the requirements, w/o actually providing the fuel for the summon, when i could use a one-card combo and set up the full ritual for free? It takes up a few spots in the Extra Deck, sure, but we never really needed it, did we? We'll get into how the combo works later. Subterror Fiendess: An omni-negate from ur hand if ur able to flip a Subterror face-down, and, while on the field can flip a monster you control (including herself) to special summon a Subterror from your hand or GY. Deskbot 001: Needed for the Deskbot 003 combo. No, we r not running multiples to mitigate the chances of a garnet, we are running 2 because the combo actually uses 2. Besides, 001 isn't as much of a garnet as in other engines, as even if you draw one of them Halq can summon from the hand. Even if you drew both, it still possible to pull the combo off, it would just require a bit of luck. Prediction Princess Tarotrei: The entire reason I made the deck. Her archetype is worthless, but she alone is worth it. Gives you an option of Book of Moon or Book of Taiyou every turn at Spell Speed 2. Then, during your end phases, you can summon a flip monster from your hand or GY. She is your main target for WL Monstrosity's second effect, which is the one you will be using the most, as all of the other level nines in the deck share the attribute of EARTH. Nekroz of Unicore: Part of the Deskbot Combo. Nekroz is one of the best ritual archetypes, and Nekroz of Unicore is easily one of the best ritual monsters in the game, negating the effect of all face-up monsters that were summoned from the Extra Deck.   Spells Pre-Preparation of Rites: Practically the only reason the deck is consistent. Able to search both Tarotrei and Prediction Ritual, but can also grab Tarotrei from the GY. Terraforming: Searches The Hidden City. If this were a pure Subterror Deck, we would also use Metaverse, but since we are not completely reliant upon it, we should be fine. Prediction Ritual: Ritual Spell for Tarotrei, searchable off Pre-Prep. It has a GY effect that allows you to banish it from the GY to search a Prediction Princess monster (in this case, Tarotrei). Note that none of the effects are once-per-turn; it's just you can't use the GY effect the turn it was sent to the GY. Nekroz Kaleidoscope: My favorite Nekroz ritual spell, it lets you use an Extra Deck monster for your Ritual Summon. Part of the Deskbot Combo. World Legacy Monstrosity: I've referenced this card a few times already. It has 2 effects for you to pick from. The first allows you to special summon a level 9 monster from your hand. Can't summon a Ritual Monster, but I digress. Its second effect is the more important one. You target a level 9 monster you control and summon 2 level nine monsters from your deck, as long as the attributes and types of the monsters are different than the target's. The only drawback is that these monsters cannot attack and will be destroyed during the End Phase. So what can you do with them? Well, for starters you can flip em face down w/ Tarotrei or Guru. Or could use em for an Xyz/Link. All goes down to you and what you see as the best option. The Hidden City: Target for Terraforming, the core of any Subterror Deck. Upon activation, you can search a Subterror monster. Once per turn, you can flip a face-down Subterror face-up. Lastly, once per turn, you can flip a face-down Subterror face-up to negate an attack.   Traps Subterror Final Battle: I would like to raise this up to 3, but I still have not found a card to take out. It allows you to choose one of four effects and then resets itself afterward instead of going to the GY. The effects are: 1) Book of Taiyou for Subterror monsters 2) Book of Moon for Subterror monsters 3) Turing the ATK/DEF of a Subterror monster to its combined original ATK/DEF. Note that this boost will ignore all other changes to the monster's stats. No, you can't stack 2 Final Batle boosts on the same monster. 4) Protects all of your Subterror cards from being negated. Overall, a very solid card, searchable off of Guru, not once per turn, so setting multiple is not a problem.   Extra Deck Herald of the Arc Light: Used for the Deskbot Combo. A viable target for Foolish Burial Goods if you were to include it. True King of All Calamities: VFD for short. Easily one of the best Rank 9 Xyz monsters in the entire game. Not sure if I should up him to 3, bring him down to 1, or leave him at 2. I'll have to keep testing. Nine-Lives Cat: Similarly to VFD, a great Rank 9 considering the amount of level 9 monsters in the deck. It also allows you to summon monsters from your opponent's graveyard. It also has blanket protection that makes all of your monsters that were summoned from the GY untargetable. Gallant Granite: Used for the Deskbot Combo, but could also search out Nibiru if necessary. Accesscode Talker: You probably already know what this card does. The Deskbot Combo provides 2 attributes (Halq/WATER and Auroradon/WIND). Linkuriboh and Phoenix may not be summoned every game, but they provide 2 more attributes (DARK & FIRE). Lastly, Subterror Behemoth Fiendess is an EARTH monster, leaving only the LIGHT attribute, but we should not need 6 pops. Hopefully. Halq & Auroradon: Only purpose is the Deskbot Combo. Subterror Behemoth Fiendess: Your typical go-to monster after using WL Monstrosity. Can advance your game state in more ways than one, unbricking your hand and retrieving resources. Knightmare Phoenix & Linkuriboh: Both are debatable, but I would like to test them a bit more before tossing them out.   Side Deck The only things I would keep here are HFD, DRNM, Cosmic Cyclone, and TCBOO. The rest are all ideas and things I would like to put in the Main Deck; do not include them in your actual Side Deck.   Deskbot Combo Like I mentioned earlier, I could just toss in something like Manju and call it a day, but where is the fun in that? Now while things like Manju and Foolish Burial Goods are things I would like to include, that will have to wait for another day. For now, here is a Deskbot 003 Combo you can use instead: This Combo requires a singular Deskbot 003 in your hand. You could also use Deskbot 001 plus any other monster and make Halq, and you would get the same result. Opening a Deskbot 001 is not a brick; opening 2 of them hurts, but if you can get one of them on the field with a different monster and summon Halq, you will be fine. So without further ado:
  1.  Normal Summon Deskbot 003
  2.  Special Summon Deskbot 001
  3.  Link Summon Halq, summoning your other Deskbot 001
  4.  Link Summon Auroradon, summoning 3 tokens and reviving both Deskbot 001s
  5.  Synchro Summon into 2 Heralds of the Arc Light
  6.  Overlay them into Gallant Granite
  7.  Activate Gallant Granite's effect, detaching a Herald and searching for Pot of the Forbidden
  8.  Activate Herald's effect, searching out a Tarotrei
  9.  Activate Auroradon's effect, tributing Gallant Granite, destroying either a card your opponent controls or your final token (just make sure Gallant Granite hits the GY)
  10.  Activate the other Herald's effect, searching a Prediction Ritual
  11.  Ritual Summon Tarotrei using Pot of the Forbidden
  12.  During your End Phase, activate Tarotrei's effect to Special Summon the Pot of the Forbidden from the GY or the Flip Monster of your choice
And now you have at the very least a Tarotrei, an Auroradon, and a Flip Monster of your choice (but if you did not have any, you could still bring back Pot of the Forbidden). But let's say you had even an ounce of luck with your Deskbot 003. If you have one of the following cards: Pre-Preparation of Rites, Tarotrei, Prediction Ritual, Nekroz of Unicore, and/or Nekroz Kaledeiscope, you can go a step further a set up an active Nekroz of Unicore, alongside everything else. So how does it work? So, I can't give you a run-down of every possible route, that would take too long. Nekroz Kaledeiscope allows you to use a monster from your Extra Deck as material for a Ritual Summon. The combo above only required 2 Heralds. Here is where the third comes into play. Focus your first 2 searches from the combo on getting the Nekroz cards. If you get them before the second Herald search, go ahead and start gathering the Prediction Princess duo. Ritual Summon Nekroz Unicore, sending your third and final Herald from your Extra Deck to the GY, and then activate its effect to search for your final piece of the Prediction Princess duo, and then summon her. Overall, its an enjoyable deck. We are in a combo format right now, where the top decks intend on ending the duel within the first 4 turns of the duel. Hopefully, the format slows down a bit with the December banlist (I doubt it). All suggestions are welcome and appreciated.

deck_excerpt: Go second, say that's a cute board you set up, proceed to run train on everything. Pun intended.
deck_description:
Trains ALWAYS want to go second if you have the choice to. If you have to go first Dora is your best hope for survival with 4000 DEF and a protection quick-effect.
  • The Kaiju engine is to help break your opponents board by removing problem monsters and possibly getting you even more level 10 monsters on yours. Three Jizukiru and Gameciel to help the chances of opening one of them, and only 2 Slumbers because if you draw one Kaiju you would make the third Slumber a dead card in deck. One Kaiju card + Night Express Knight + Derricrane is usually enough for an OTK in most cases. Kaiju the problem, summon Express, Special Derricrane, XYZ into Gustav and burn for 2000. Then use Derricrane's effect to destroy the Kaiju, overlay into Liebe, activate effect to make ATK 6000 and punch for game.
  • Dark Ruler is also a really good board breaker. Your opponent has a 15 negate board? Who cares!? Dark Ruler them then proceed to run over each of their monsters with Liebe because it can attack monsters up to the number of materials it has +1. This deck can easily spit out a 4 material Liebe to wipe an entire board. Dark Ruler + Slumber also clears boards super fast. You won't be able to OTK but you can at least set up your board to counter what they might do next turn.
  • Switchyard is your bread and butter. Don't have the level 10 you need? Just pitch what you don't want and add what you do. Switchyard gets shut down hard by Ash Blossom, but that's where Triple Tactical Talents comes in. They Ash your search, and you say I'll draw 2 anyways, thanks. Switchyard + Pegasus +Bullet Train = 3 level 10s. Switchyard to pitch Bullet adding Derricrane. Summon Pegasus, activate effect to special Bullet from grave chaining Derricrane. If you already have those three monsters in hand, pitch Bullet to add Bullet, then do the combo again. Only this time you activate the second Bullet in hand for 4 level 10s. That's a Liebe and a Dora in one turn
  • Urgent Schedule is one of the best cards in the deck. Special summon 2 monsters for free that triggers all of your other monsters and spells? Yes please. Depending how good or bad your hand is, you can easily end on a Liebe with Dora protection. Or, it'll save you during the battle phase by summoning two monsters to absorb some damage. The two best monsters to summon off this are Ruffian and Bullet Train because of their end phase effects to get the cards you need into your hand.
  • Skill Drain is usually a sided card in most decks, especially in go second decks because of how slow it is to active it. But it has won me many a duel by making all my monsters giant beats sticks. All the big trains activate in hand and once they hit the field they usually lose attack damage or make you destroy stuff to attack, but with Skill Drain they stay big beaters and basically summon themselves for free.
  • One funny combo I pull off once in a while happens when I have Switchyard on field, Urgent Schedule set, a level 10 in the grave, and a derricrane in hand. During your opponent's end phase activate Urgent Schedule to summon two monsters. Then, activate Switchyards effect to summon a level 4 and it becomes a level 10. Summon Pegasus, make it a 10, then activate Pegasus' effect to summon the level 10 from grave chaining Derricrane. Boom, 5 monsters summoned during your opponent's turn and they can't even Nibiru you. Proceed to make Dora first on your turn, then do your Gustav/Liebe combo without worry because of Dora's protection.
  • The side deck is basically to help curb whatever is meta at the moment, with the exception of Summon Limit. Summon Limit is the only card I would never change in the side deck. Summon Limit is for when you know they are going to make you go first, or when you feel lucky and throw them off by saying you'll go first. Go first, make Dora, set Summon Limit, watch them die inside when you activate it on their second summon. After that, all you have to do is overlay Liebe as your one summon and proceed to beat everything down.

deck_excerpt: Paleo Frogs to swarm and stun the opponent, and go into big XYZ/links
deck_description: So Dzeef made a video about this deck, and I decided to make a sort of variant on it. This is more so a stun and control based deck, using the Paleos to fuck wit the opponent as you swarm the field. Deck guide. 3x Swap Frog- graveyard setup and easy special summon, can also serve to get out more with an extra normal summon. great card 3x Dupe Frog- pops up and searches, you'll most likely link it away or something to get it's search off 3x Poison Draw Frog- also gives a nice draw when linked away or tributed for an effect, also doesn't have a once per turn on it's draw 3x Ronintoadin- Again, easy special summon for swarming 3x Treeborn Frog- Can special summon himself for swarming, although using him can be a bit inconsitent due to the Paleos 3x Tradetoad- Monster recovery and graveyard setup in one 3x Ash Blossom- just dont play lol 2x Ghost Ogre- helps to destroy strong shit that the frogs can't get over themselves 1x Foolish Burial- gy setup 1x Monster Reborn- Utilizes the GY for more swarming 3x Canadia- flips down a problem monster so it cant activate it's effects or anything, won't work on links but can still work on problem cards like Conducter Tyranno 3x Dinomischuis- GY setup with the discard and banishes a problem card 3x Marella- GY setup for the other Paleos, so you can set up easier 3x Olenoides- destroys backrow against problem decks like Eldlich 3x Pikai- Draw power and Gy setup, super underappreciated imo 3x Trap Trick- basically searches out your traps way easier if there's one you need but didn't open Extra deck 2x Toadally Awesome- Swarming, GY setup, and negations against decks like Eldlich. Great card 2x Opabinia- searches and allows you to activate Paeleoz from hand, which is amazing 2x Anomalocaris- GY setup, draw, and destruction for cards you can't just beat over 2x Linkurboh- can be linked into from Tradetoad or Treeborn frog, then links into secure gardna 2x Secure Gardna- links into from Linkuribo, helps to stun the opponent heavily 2x Apolousa- Great negates and all around great card 2x I;P masqureana- link up into Apolousa Playing guide The deck isn't super complex or anything, as it doesn't have any long winded combos. You want to set up a strong backrow of Paelos and swarm the field with frogs by dumping them and special summoning them, then going into either A) Toadally Awesome for a normal grind game or B) Apolousa to negate and wittle them down quicker. the Apolousa route takes much more resources but can wittle down the opponent quicker, and Toadally grinds slower and swarms much better but still takes less resources, so it's up to your opening hand and GY setup to which path you want to take. Afterwards, stun your opponent heavily with the Paleos and special summon them later to make more XYZ (or links), to stun your opponent and eventually OTK them. Note: you'll want to go first for the more control based focus of the deck, and the deck costs around 139 American dollars all together, not accounting for the side deck. Also, I think this deck might come into the spotlight more and maybe be a good rouge contender, although time will tell Any suggestions are appreciated. Have a good day

deck_excerpt: This is TeamSamuraiX1's Zoodiac Divine Zeus Deck Profile with some small alterations due to him leaving 1 card out of his deck profile.  https://www.
deck_description:
This is a copy of TeamSamuraiX1's Zoodiac Divine Zeus Deck Profile with 1 card change due to him forgetting to completely have a 40 card main deck (his deck profile only had 39 main deck cards). Combo #1: Zoodiac Raptier/Thoroughblade + Ramram The point of this combo is to get Megaclops onto the field as quickly as possible.
  1. Assuming you have Raptier in your hand at the start of the turn, normal summon it, activate its effect to send Ramram to the GY.
  2. Xyz summon Chakanine using Raptier in DEF position.
  3. Activate Chakanine to send Raptier to the GY and special summon Ramram in DEF position. 
  4. Xyz summon Drident on top of Chakanine in DEF position.
  5. Activate Drident to send Chakanine to the GY to destroy Ramram.
  6. Activate Ramram's effect to special summon Chakanine form the GY to the field in DEF position.
  7. Xyz Tigermortar on top of Drident in DEF position.
  8. Activate Tigermortan to detach Drident and attach Ramram from the GY to Chakanine.
  9. Activate Chakanine to detach Ramram to special summon Drident from your GY into DEF position.
  10. Send those 3 Xyz monsters to the GY to link summon Megaclops on the right EMZ.
Combo #2: Any Zoodiac Monster The purpose of this combo is to get Drident out on the field asap.
  1. Assume you have Ramram in your hand and normal summon it.
  2. Xyz summon Boarbow on top of Ramram.
  3. Xyz summon Tigermortar on top of Boarbow.
  4. Xyz summon Drident on top of Tigermortar in DEF position
Comb0 #3: Any Zoodiac Monster Similar to combo 2.
  1. Normal summon any Zoodiac monster.
  2. Xyz summon Boarbow on top of that Zoodiac monster.
  3. Enter BP, and attack with Boarbow, assuming your opponent can't stop you.
  4. Enter MP2, Xyz summon Divine Arsenal on top of Boarbow in DEF position.
  5. From here on out you can have your hand traps ready as well as any of the traps you can set in MP2.
  6. Then you can start to control the field and go end the game.
  7. Steps 1 to 4 is to help set up your board if you go second.

deck_excerpt: A decent mid-range deck that uses the Twins and a Code Talker package for disruption and draw power.
deck_description: This a relatively easy deck to pilot, as long as you stay aware of the Fiend Lock after using the revive effect of the Evil Twin, and make sure to not lock your own monsters out of effects because of Knightmare Gryphon. You generally want to make Heatsoul + Conflict with Evil Twin Kiskil on the field and Lilla in the grave for your opponents turn. This often involves reviving Kisikil on your turn for a draw, and then linking the two into another Kisikil. If you have access to Challenge, you can make Knightmare Gryphon to floodgate your opponent or Unchained Abomination for more disruption, while still being able to revive the Twins on your opponents turn. Accesscode helps end games, and Saros Eresh Kurnugias can link off a hard to get rid of monster, as well as having some solid protection and negation.  This deck is also a work in progress, and I have various versions with different ratios or cards, such as Cynet Regression instead of Conflict, which does not rely on a Code Talker being on the field and doubles down on the "pop-and-draw" aspect of the Twins. One with 3 Code Generator and 1 Sea Archiver as a secondary target, for after Dotscaper has been expended, and one without Lilla Treat, because she wasn't revealed yet.  The deck has a pretty low ceiling, but I find it quite enjoyable. And if you have any questions regarding it, please ask, as my descriptions tend to be pretty basic.

deck_excerpt: Atlantean Mermails v2 Electric Boogaloo!! - A deck that has rarely failed me in real life and can combat a variety of situations. Almost every hand is
deck_description: There are many more terrrors at sea than pirates and ghost ships, from the depths rise warmongering sea serpents, Fish-people and Sea-people. This is the place where you can see which fish in the seven seas work best together. I will be covering each and every card / archetype used (Including the side this time), telling you all the info you need to know about this particular deck. I am going to be laying it out slightly differently this time, instead of doing it card by card (for the main deck) I will be doing them in archetypes / groups. If you have any questions about the deck please let me know :), I will not be going over their effects individually unless i deem it neccessary so please check out my 1st Decklist for that.   - Main Deck: Atlanteans: The "Atlantean" engine I run is a 3:3:3 of <Prince>, <Dragoon> and <Infantry>. By this point you should already know what they do and why I am running 3 of them, however <Infantry> isn't usually played at 3 and that is what I shall use this section to explain. Running <Infantry> at 2 wasnt very bricky however I run out of Neptabyss targets super quickly at 2, running the 3rd just means I can use <Neptabyss'> effect an extra time before running out of targets. It also means I have an additional face-up pop. I can afford to put an extra copy of <Infantry> in the deck because I took most of the bricking cards out of the deck. The other 2 cards are staples to any "Atlantean" deck and I shouldn't have to explain why they are being played at 3 xD. Mermails: Some people might be confused with my choice to run the Mermail engine at 3:1:1 as it is usualy run with 1 copy of <Gunde> aswell. I decided not to run the gunde as I would see it too often and never be able to use its effect at the right time, I would also like to see alot of other cards in the deck over this card. The other 3 cards are the same, <Teus> is a starter we want to see in our starting hand as much as possible, <Pike> and <Megalo> are searchable so they are played as 1 of's. Deep Sea: I run both cards at 3 for a 3:3 ratio, technically both of these cards are starters for the deck with <Diva> being the primary NS of the deck and <Minstrel> being a ditcher for dragoons. I am running <Minstrel> at three because its so versatile: it deals with handtraps, has multiple ways of ditching "Atlanteans" and it can recur WATER monsters back from the GY to the deck with the primary target usually being <Dragoons>. Frogs: Like the "Mermail" engine the ratios I am using may surprise some people. With a 2:1 "Frog" monster ratio the deck does not draw into them all that much, which is the idea. This strategy is great for both <Toad> plays and extending other WATER plays, however <Swog> doesn't activate the ditch effects of my"Atlantean" cards and so it can cause issues with the starting hand. Regardless I have had great success running this ratio, but if you wish you could add another <Swog>. Honourary AtlaMails: As is tradition I am running a 1:1 ration of <Moulinglacia> and <Lappis>. I shouldnt have to explain why but they are both searchable of dragoons. With <Moulinglacia> hand looping the ooponent and being a level 8 (Synchro plays)  he is great at gaining advantage over the opponent, Whilst lappis is Useful for rounds when you don't see <Diva> for the <Halq> plays. Generic Water: A ratio of 2:1 is used to help make Synchro plays after first turn and extend combos. <Spirit> is an extender that can help make <Bahamut> or a Link monster. Spells: For draw power I run a 3:2:1 ratio of <Moray>, <Aria> and <Avarice> respectively. <Moray> is a +0 card advantage but it cycles through the deck reliantly with the amount of Water monsters in the deck the only issue this card has is if you draw it as a top deck. <Aria> on the other hand is a great top deck and an amazing draw card as it allows you to add either <Dragoons> or <Infantry> depending on what is neccessary. It can also add <Diva> or <Neptabyss> but this isnt as good a search. I also use 1 <Avarice> which is useful for Longer grind games, it recurs <neptabyss> and other neccessary pieces. As a tech choice I run 1:1 of <1 for 1> and <Instant Fusion> as they extend the plays I can make or free up a NS. Instant fusion can be used both agressively and defensively in this deck dependant on which Fusion you summon. As Interuption I play 1 <Called by> and 3 <Chalice>. The 1 of is to add a 4th way of preventing the deck from being hand trapped and the 3 of is to stop your opponents plays. Now you may be wondering... "Why is he using chalice, just use imperm!?". <Chalice> is a BTEC imperm and it works really well, besides not being able to stop your opponents first turn play if you go 2nd it works the exact same way. In fact <chalice> is what comes out when Dark Ruler + Imperm have a card baby. It can be set and activated to stop opponent plays during their turn or if you are going second you can bait a negate / prevent an opponents monster from using its effects. <Chalice> is one of our SD targets, but I will get to that later... Traps: Oh would you look at that... there aren't any xD -ExtraDeck: Fusions: <TrishF>, <Mudragon> and <Restrict> are all fantastic fusions for this deck all though it is unlikely you will summon 2 of them :( <TrishF> is an essential part of the <VFD> combo and can be reliably summoned on the 1st turn, his effects are useless to the deck but his lvl isn't. <Muddragon> Is the defensive side of <Instant Fusion> I was talking about earlier in the article. His effect prevents your monsters from being targeted by your opponent's effects and he is a level 4 so once he has finished protecting your monsters he can be linked or xyz'd off the board. <restrict is <Mudragons> Offensivc counterpart to <Instan Fusion> and can be used to get rid of some pesky monsters on the field, because it is a level 1 it can be used to summon <TrishS> or <TrishF>. Synchros: <TrishS>, <Croc>, <Dragite> and <Whale> all have their places in my deck as solid 1-of options. <TrishS> and <Croc> are both Lvl9 so they are used as material for <VFD> however <Croc> can also be summoned back by <Coral> making him a recursive destruction effect. <Dragite> is mostly only used against the decks that use pivotal spells, like Mystic Mine or Dream Mirror. as for <Whale> he only gets used every know and then to destroy your opponents field in one swoop. Xyz's: <VFD>, <Bahamut> and <Toad> is what your first turn will look like most of the time. <Vfd> is made with either lvl9 Synchro and <TrishF> really easily. <Toad> is just as easily made with <Bahamut> as <VFD> is, it can also be made with the "Frog" engine. Links: With only 4 Link monsters in the deck, they have to be good, and they are! <Halq> and <Linkross> are used to make <VFD> this is especiallyhelped by the tokens that <Linkross> creates. <Coral> is used for recursion and is an all round great Water support card. Lastly <Alacia> is summoned as a searcher for <Teus> for next turn, this can also disrupt the opponent if <Infantry> is ditched. - Side Deck: Forbidden Chalice / Aqua Spirit / Moulinglacia are the main deck cards that can be sided the easiest. <Kaiju> - Side 3 of these cards in when (1) + (2): 1) your opponent has cards that are unaffected by your effects. 2) Your going 2nd <Desert Locust> - Side this card in when: 1) you know your going first <Abyss Dweller> - Side this card in when: 1) You are playing against a deck that relies on thee GY , Like BA. 2) Your going 1st <Raigeki> - Side this card in when: 1) the deck your playing against spams the board. <Feather Duster> - Side this card in when: 1) your opponent is playing alot of spells. <Dark Ruler> - Side this card in when (1) + (2): 1) Your going 2nd. 2) your opponent builds a big board with lots of negates. <Cosmic Cyclone> - Side this card in when (1) + (2): 1) Your playing against a deck that is reliant on spells and traps. 2) you play against mystic mine. <Mizuchi> - Side this card in when (1) + (2): 1) Your opponent is going 2nd. 2) your opponent relies on non-continous / field spells Please comment and suggest what things could be improved :P

deck_excerpt: Post Banlist "Domain Monarchs" deck with maximum possible consistency. Unlimitied Pantheism makes Pot of Desires a viable option.
deck_description:
I used to be a big fan of this archetype, having invested a lot of time and love into building my own version for a good couple of years, then stopped playing it during late 2018. That was the point where I realized that, even at full power, nothing but new support could ever bring the king of bricks back to their former glory; the meta is way faster, way more consistent, and with cards like Lightning Storm, Dark Ruler No More and Forbidden Droplet becoming the new powerful staples along Ash Blossom and Infinite Impermanence (which already gave Monarch players a pretty hard time to deal with), I'm confident that Domain Monarchs have been reduced to an archetype to play with, for fun, against your friends. That being said, since there's honestly no way to take consistent wins against more competitive decks, I decided to focus on making a build that is, at least, as consistent as it can get. You will still brick from time to time, it doesn't have a perfect search engine like other archetypes do, but at least you'll be able to do its main functions and get the feel that you're playing "pure" Monarchs.   The main differences between this and my previous build are:
  1. Having 3x copies of Pantheism allows for using Pot of Desires as a viable draw-card, without the danger of killing the only copy of the best card in the deck.
  2. Same goes for the Prime Monarch, where I have 2x copies this time around, which run better than 1x with an unlimited Pantheism, hence tribute fodder is better.
  3. Also, 3x copies of Ehther means easier to search, though running 6x lvl.8 Monarchs instead of 4x makes it slightly more dangerous to brick.
  4. Last but not least, running 2x copies of Majesty's instead of Vanity's suits Tenacity better, though I still believe that Tenacity is very occational and not that great of a card. Plus, the lack of Allure of Darkness opens slots for less Dark monsters, which is also a reason why I chose to run Mithra instead of Kaiser Vorse Raider; Pantheism and Desires bring more consistency, meaning you can more easily draw Monarchs and not rely on KVR's double nature.
  It's worth noting that I choose to main only 1x copy of Stormforth, as opening with even 1x when going first bricks hard. I save the remaining 2x copies for when going 2nd, while the rest of my Side Deck gives plenty of option to counter both monster-spams and spell/trap-spams.
First step in customizing via packs.

deck_excerpt: Paleo Frogs rely on a large number of traps, combined with the Frog archetype in order to disrupt the opponent and their plays.
deck_description: Paleo Frogs consist of the 9 best frog cards, and many traps (most of which are part of the Paleozoic archetype) in the Main Deck. Their main strategy is to disrupt the opponent's plays with cards like Infinite Impermanence, Paleozoic Canadia, Paleozoic Dinomischus,  and the Solemn series of counter traps. Using such a large amount of traps allows them to take advantage of the effects of the Paleozoic traps from the GY, which special summon them as level 2 aqua type monsters. This just so happens to coincide with Toadally Awesome's summoning conditions, which is a powerful negation card. However, there is a plethora of rank 2 XYZ monsters to take advantage of. Post Phantom Rage, the deck doesn't actually change much. I just wanted an excuse to post this. But, it does add the new TCG card, Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, which is an incredible piece of XYZ support. While being slightly situational, its ability to nuke the field effortlessly can't be ignored.

deck_excerpt: Constantly revive your Archfiends and use the Extra Deck for additional destruction!
deck_description: Hey! It's the Archfiend Guy Again :D  This deck is all about beatdown and stun! At its core, we summon high attack level 8 fiend monsters such as Archfiend Empress and Curse Necrofear, to help overwhelm your opponent with destruction effects and pure attack power. The Extra Deck in this build is mainly used as utility for the likes of Pot of Disparity, and Dogmatika Punishment, but we can also go into Rank 8s such as Dingirsu and Zombiestein (sometimes you just need a beater!). There's plenty of cards to help mill and search, such as Dark Spirit's Mastery, Void Apocalypse, Foolish Burial, and Danger! Mothman. The Dark Spirit monsters help revive your fiends and maintain pressure, whereas cards such as Skill Drain, Gozen Match and Mystic Mine help render your opponent powerless. Mystic Mine works very well with Archfiends, as they rely on destroying themselves. Therefore, you can pop cards on the field with monsters such as Archfiend Emperor, only for him to get destroyed as well, ensuring that you always have less monsters until you need to push for lethal! In addition, we also run 3 copies of Successor Soul and 2 copies of Zoa to send monsters rather than destroy. Since Archfiend Emperor destroys himself, you can use his effect to pop cards, then send an additional card through Successor Soul and then rewarding your efforts with a 2600 beatstick! Check out the deck profile here Enjoy, and until next time I'll see you around!

deck_excerpt: This deck is all about using Melffy and friends to save the forest!
deck_description: This deck is all about using Melffy and friends to save the forest!   Hide-and Seek!: You ALWAYS want to get out Melffy of the Forest and use it to grab Melffy Hide-and-Seek as soon as possible. Hide-and-Seek, other than being Melffys favorite game, allows you to save your beast monsters from being destroyed by card effects the first time each turn. It also allows you to shuffle three beasts with different names into your deck from your GY and draw a card. Melffy of the Forest lets you search cards, but also allows you to cancel the effects of a summoned monster once per turn if it activates a Melffy's ability to go back to your hand. This is why you should always have at least one Melffy monster out at all times. (which is VERY easy to do!)   The Melffys!: You pretty much always want to have Melffy Puppy out. This lets you grab Kalantosa, Mystical Beast of the Forest, activating its ability to destroy a card on the field. Melffy Catty lets you search cards you need to add to your hand. This very useful to grab a Rescue Cat or the Boss, Alpacaribou, Mystical Beast of the Forest. Melffy Fenny lets you summon from your hand completing the combo to get out Alpacaribou or any other monster stuck in your hand. Melffy Pony and Melffy Rabbi are mostly just fuel for Obedience Schooled or Xyz. Melffy Mommy is interesting and can be utilized really well for direct damage, a wall or Melffy Playhouse.   ...and Friends!: Naturia Beast is what you will mostly use Rescue Cat for summoning Valerifawn, Mystical Beast of the Forest and either Mine Mole or Crusadia Leonis to syncro for Naturia Beast in one turn. Nimble Beaver helps you get out your Xyz and I have subbed them for Amazoness Pet Baby Tiger which works better for Obedience Schooled (and keeps everyone EARTH) Missus Radiant is your go to for Link summoning. The attack boost is a huge help and with the help of Scapegoat you can summon both at once for little effort! Number 64: Ronin Raccoon Sandayu is a big help against foes with a lot attack power. It's tokens can fight the toughest boss monsters and with the help of Missus Radiant, Closed Forest, or Ayers rock Sunrise you can overtake them easily! Melffy Mommy has a huge pocket that works sort of like a bag of holding. She likes to turn it inside out for a Dark Hole magic attack that, if Melffy Hide-and-Seek is active, only gets rid of your opponents monsters! Aussa the Earth Charmer, Immovable likes to wander into the forest every once in awhile, but mostly to chase random creatures around for fun   I hope I covered everything! This deck is all about getting cards on and off the field and being cute and having fun! Though sometimes you need some protecting from the guardians of the forest. NOTE: I just got Joyous Melffys and I haven't played with it yet, but wanted it in there anyway

deck_excerpt: A deck featuring the "Flamvell" archetype, which tries to overwhelm the opponent with beatdown, burn and its main playmaking card in form of "Rekindli
deck_description:
This is my take at a "Flamvell" deck. "Flamvell" and its sub-archetypal "Neo-Flamvell" are a completely Fire-based group that almost exclusively consists out of monsters. The archetype is often seen as the alpha version of "Laval", who just so happened to be able to use their main playmaker in form of "Rekindling" as much as "Flamvell" could. Strategy-wise, the monsters feature a mix of Special Summoning, burn damage and beatdown-/battle-focussed effects, but the overall age of the archetype(s) is clear for anyone to see. "Flamvells" was one of the first archetypes to receive Synchro monsters, showcasing how old the archetype actually is, and the loose group of members really does not have that many similar factors and strategies to work with in unison. Nonetheless, I tried to build something with them and I feel like the deck at least tries to make the best out of what the archetype has to offer.

One cannot talk about "Flamvell" without mentioning "Flamvell Firedog". This 1900 ATK critter can summon monsters from the deck if it manages to destroy something in battle, which is rather mediocre from a modern standpoint but really one of the best cards the archetype has to offer. Together with the other key card in the deck, "Red Resonator", you can actually manage to summon Synchro and Link monsters in turn one, despite the fact that "Flamvells" are terribly slow. "Red Resonator" also has the huge benefit of having 200 DEF and therefore being revivable via "Rekindling", and as an added bonus it even heals your life points when Special summoned, giving the deck an odd amount of survivability in certain situations. "Neo-Flamvell Lady" is the newest support card and brings disruption and graveyard setup, both well received in the archetype. The single copy of "Flamvell Archer" serves both as a Level 3 Tuner monster, as well as a potential ATK boost after a "Rekindling" play. The last archetypal monster in the Main Deck is "Neo-Flamvell Origin", who can technically serve as further swarming, just in a fairly limited amount of scenarios.

This alone does not make the deck though: I added two copies of "Cataclysmic Scorching Sunburner" and two copies "Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Stag" to the deck; the first one provides a small amount of burn damage while being a sizeable beatstick that can summon itself when you lose resources, while "Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Stag" is a big beater that can enter the field rather easily by getting rid of opposing Extra Deck monsters. The two copies of "Volcanic Shell" are just there to be ditched via "Neo-Flamvell Lady", but they do provide further deck thinning and a card to discard if necessary. Lastly, the "Guerilla Kite" might seem odd, but it is one of the few Level 4 Fire Tuners in the game, has more attack than "Flamvell Magician", the necessary 200 DEF for "Rekindling" revives and a small burn damage to edge you closer to OTKable life point numbers.

The backrow consists entirely of Spell cards in order to make the deck run smoother and faster. Three copies of "Resonator Call" are there to make sure that you can pull the summoning of two monsters turn one off, two "Pot of Desires" and one "Pot of Avarice" are reasonably priced draw options, "Reasoning" is another swarming tool, "Monster Reborn" can fetch stuff back for attacks and Extra Deck summons, while "Raigeki", "Harpie's Feather Duster" and "Twin Twisters" all destroy opposing cards that you might struggle with. The main star of the show are the three copies of "Rekindling", which can turn the deck from a weak pile of cards into an actual thread, either by kicking for enough damage to allow for an OTK or by using the summoned monsters for various Extra Deck shenanigans to gain board control that way. To allow "Rekindling" to work at full potential, there are also options like "Slash Draw", "Card Destruction" and "Performapal Popperup" which all fill the graveyard with revivable monster cards.

The Extra Deck features a number of options to either get rid of certain threats on the opposing side of the field or to support the Extra Deck summon chain after the successful "Rekindling" play. For the former there are "Knightmare Phoenix", "Salamangreat Heatleo", "Brionac, Dragon of the Ice Barrier" and "Black Rose Dragon", all taking care of certain threats that might come up. For the swarming, there are three copies of "Duelittle Chimera", which I previously ran at a lower copy count but I found that summoning all three is actually possible and sometimes even very helpful. "Hiita the Fire Charmer, Ablaze" and "Saryuja Skull Dread" can transform pretty much any monster into more helpful option, while the new "Infernity Doom Archfiend" can become a pretty solid beater/destruction option if you play your cards right.

It has to be said that this is not a competitively viable deck as "Flamvell" is a rather lackluster archetype; in fact, I would say that they do not get even close to anything meta-related in terms of power level or consistency. However, for Casual rounds this deck should perform just fine and it was in all honesty the maximum I thought there was to get out of the archetype without simply throwing lots of money cards at it. If you are interested in the archetype and might even want to try giving your own "Flamvell" deck a spin, I invite you to look at my "Flamvell" analysis on my blog here: https://cubiccreativity.wordpress.com/2020/10/03/archetype-analysis-neo-flamvell/

This deck was designed with budget players in mind. The main deck is valued at a little less than 40$ USD, and the Extra Deck is around the same. But, any cards in the Extra Deck can be swapped out, or you can alternatively have no Extra Deck at all!

deck_excerpt: There is no board these guys can't break.
deck_description: This is a going second deck, right? SURELY THEY CAN'T MAKE A COMPETENT BOARD TURN ONE, RIGHT? With the addition of Ancient Warriors - Rebellious Lu Feng, they actually can. With this mostly being a going second deck, everything depends on the opponent's board so it's hard to write a guide on how to exactly play. The most common line of play I do is first normal summoning Ancient Warriors - Virtuous Liu Xuan, which summons an Ancient Warriors - Masterful Sun Mou, which adds either a Lu Feng or a Ancient Warriors - Ingenious Zhuge Kong, or anything else, really. Now that we have 2 or more bodies, we can make Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords, which adds any card from the archetype directly to your hand. A very cool thing about Ancient Warriors are the effects they activate when another Ancient Warriors monster activates their effect. Some of these effects include bouncing, negating or destroying backrow. Also be sure to bait out any negates and think of a backup plan before trying to break the whole board. Side deck is subject to change. You can play whatever you want in it, really.

deck_excerpt: The Lunalight deck you've been looking for brought to you by yours truly.
deck_description: **Before we get to the strategy, here's a quick explanation on my deck : I'm only running 2 Foolish Burial Goods and 2 Fire Formation - Tenki In this deck particularly, you don't need to run 3. I have ran 3 before, I decided I prefer them at 2. It opens up more plays for me and makes space for my extremely important backrow removal. MST is a great spell. It's a quick spell with no costs, and has a classic feeling. Twin Twisters require discarding, and Cosmic Cyclone requires you to pay 1000 LP to banish. The discarding effect is great, it puts things in my graveyard, but I need a hand to play with. I don't run more than 1 TT. and I haven't come across a spell/trap that I so badly needed to banish. Destroying it is enough. Presumably there won't be another turn for your opponent to use the effect of whatever spell/trap you destroyed. I main deck Sphere Mode of Ra, Kaiju, and Zoo King Alpha because, why not? why should I have to lose game 1 to bring them in for game 2? Why can't I win game 1 with the help of Kaiju? Why must I lose that first game to Dragun, Infinity, Borreload and Apollousa? or to UCT, Laggia, VFD and Wind Barrier Statue? I don't have to. I can run whatever removal I need in my main deck. I don't need a whole entire 40 card archetype in my deck. I only need about 18 - 20 Lunalight cards,  10 utility cards, and the other stuff can be anything. I prefer backrow removal and things to deal with monsters. You bait an effect here, bait an effect there, Kaiju this, negate that, and proceed with your play.   Now that that's out the way, onto the strategy : I prefer to search Tenki via Tiger King's effect. Tiger King is good for 2 reasons : 1 . Searches your Beast-Warriors. 2 . Negates the effects of all non Beast-Warriors. In other words, your opponent will be forced to negate if they want to protect their monsters. You can OTK without normal summoning, it is possible and I have done it. It's why I main deck Sphere Mode of Ra. I don't need that normal summon to pull it off. and then Tiger King will just negate Sphere Mode, so you can attack it for game. **Dark World Dealings triggers your Lunalight monster's effects. Do NOT use Lunalight Fusion as your main fusion card. Lunalight Fusion uses a MATERIAL from the DECK, use it to SETUP your GRAVEYARD. Do NOT miss out on a play because you used Lunalight Fusion to summon Sabre Dancer. Lunalight Fusion triggers the effects of your Lunalight monsters. So send Emerald Bird from your deck to activate her effect to summon one Lunalight (only Kaleido Chick is worth this summon) from the graveyard or banished zone. Or use it to send Yellow Marten to activate her effect to add a Lunalight trap from your deck to your hand. This trap can be discarded a million different ways. **Psst, The only way you should be fusion summoning is through Wolf. Why Wolf? Because Wolf BANISHES your KALEIDO CHICK, which has an effect that ACTIVATES when she is BANISHED. This effect reads : " If this card is banished: You can activate this effect; this turn, your opponent's cards and effects cannot be activated during the Battle Phase." *Drops the mic* *And his Diet Coke* Only go for game if you banish Kaleido Chick, otherwise don't risk attacking. It's a One Turn Kill. Not Dogmatika Invoked Shaddoll. Go for the One Turn Kill if and only if you banish Kaleido Chick. Thy Goal : To get Leo out as soon as possible AND secure the OTK. Steps To Achieve Thy Goal : 1 . Protect yourself first. Use the Kaijus and Droplets to protect yourself from getting negated. This deck can bait and deal with negates pretty well, but realistically no one is surviving 7 interruptions. USE the mf'ing Kaijus and Zoo King Alpha and Sphere Mode to protect yourself from threats. 2 . Get Kaleido Chick in Hand, Field and/or Graveyard ASAP. The more the merrier. 3 . Get Wolf in Hand or Graveyard (Field is OK too but you will need to use Yellow Marten to put him back in your hand. Least optimal scenario) 4 . Have some way to Special Summon Blue Cat, either from Hand or from Graveyard. Blue Cat will double Leo's original attack. 5 . (Optional) After you're done and have successfully brought Leo's ATK points to 7000 and have checked off everything in the list, Link into the Link 4 Tribrigade monster to banish something off the field. Bonus points for banishing Dragun. 6 . Attack and say GGWP. Remember to be humble and respect your opponent.

There are 3 ways to win with this deck, first is with Destiny Board's effeck, the second is using Curse Necrofear & Dark Necrofear's effects to give you the advantage over the opponent, the last is to have the opponent burn themselves with Dark Sanctuary if they can't remove it. First step is to get Curse Necrofear into the graveyard, there are multiple ways to do this:  1. Summon Tour Guide From the Underworld & use her effect to summon Fiendish Rhino Warrior, go into Link or XYZ play & send Fiendish Rhino Warrior to the graveyard & use his effeck to send Curse Necrofear to the graveyard, you can also send one of the Drak Spirit's there if you use Cherubini.  2. Use Foolish Burial to send Fiendish Rhino Warrior the the graveyard & then use his effect to send Curse Necrofear there.  3. Use Trade in to send Curse Necrofear to the graveyard.  Dark Sanctuary & Battle Fader are the deck's stall cards, after you summon Battle Fader, if you have Destiny Board/Spirit Message's & Sentence of Doom set up, get rid of it & use Sentance of Doom's effect to return it. Terraforming & Metaverse will help you get it.  Even if Destiny Board gets destroyed you can use Dark Spirit's Mastery's graveyard effect to send them back to the Deck & draw more cards potentially going +4 also & it's probably better your opponent waste's their resources trying to stop Destiny Board, it you do manage to get Destiny Board & 3 of the other Spirit messages use Sentence of Doom to place the last one & win the Duel.  Finally there's Curse Necrofear & Dark Necrofear, use the Dark Spirits effects to summon Curse Necrofear from the graveyard & preferably get it destroyed if you have face up spell & trap cards at the end of the turn it will return potentially destroy up to 5 of the opponents cards. Dark Necrofear needs to be summoned properly first by banishing 3 fiend type monsters, but you should have no trouble getting fiend type monsters into the graveyard & you can use Sentence of Doom or Curse Necrofear summoning condition to retrieve them. if both of them get destroyed on the same you can take control of on of the opponent's monsters and destroy a card on their field since Dark Necrofear counts as a spell when equipped to an opponent's monster. When either of them get destroyed use the Dark Spirit's graveyard effects to add the to your hand allowing you to summon them again.

deck_excerpt: Mostly a fun deck that can build a decent board.
deck_description:
The goal is to end with Herald of the Arc Light, Borreload Savage Dragon equiped with Dragon Buster and Zombie World on the field with Doomking Balerdroch in the GY. This deck has several different ways to get to its end board, so there is no one specific combo to get there. But I'll try to explain the kind of route you'd want to take.
  • In most cases you want to try to get Striker Dragon out as soon as possible with Rokket Tracer either in hand or GY, the preferred way to do this is by using Chaos Space or Quick Launch.
  • Search Boot Sector Launch with Striker Dragon, and if Tracer is in the GY use Strikers effect to get Tracer to the hand.
  • Use Boot Sector Launch to special summon Tracer. Then you can use Tracer together with any extender to go into Halqifibrax, then use Halqifibrax's effect to summon out Plaguespreader Zombie.
  • Link Halqifibrax into Linkross and summon 2 tokens with it's effect. Then synchro summon Martial Metal Marcher using Plague spreader and one of the tokens. You can use Martial's effect to summon Tracer back out again. With this you already have the setup for Herald of the Arc Light and have a lv4 tuner ready for Borreload Savage Dragon.
From this point it's all dependend on which extenders you opened with or were able to get throughout making combo's. If you have Necroworld Banshee in the graveyard or Zombie World in hand, you could revive Plaguespreader through his effect, activate Zombie World and use Plaguespreader and Linkross to go into Union Carrier for the Dragon Buster. When you get stuck but you are able to go into a lv8 synchro there is the possibility to go into Chaos Ruler to mill some cards and get a new card in hand. It's risky but can help you out, additionally Chaos Ruler can be used as an extender through his floating effect. I know it's not really the most helpful explaination but I hope you'll get the basic gist of this deck and have fun playing around with it.

deck_excerpt: Amazoness cards with a rock side-theme for fusion-, synchro- and link- summons.
deck_description:
Monsters: Amazoness Queen - The best Amazoness-monster-card to play, that makes Amazoness-monster-cards undestroyable from battle-damage.
  1. It can be summoned from the deck with Amazoness Village if Amazoness Pet Liger, Amazoness Empress or Amazoness Queen gets destroyed by battle or card effect.
  2. It gets summoned from the Hand, GY or Deck if Amazoness Empress gets destroyed,
  3. It can be summoned with Amazoness Princess, also when Amazoness Princess declares an attack, you can attack monsters with higher atk this way because you can't get destroyed when you attack after the effect, but you will get battle-damage from it, and the effect must work.
  4. It can be summoned with Amazoness Onslaught from the hand, when it's activated in every Battle-Phase
Amazoness Princess - A good card to play form the start hand because you can get Amazoness Village or Amazoness Onslaught with it, if you have another Amazoness-monster-card, you could also get Amazoness Spy to special summon it. Amazoness Spy - Can be special summoned to get more monsters on the field, can also be fusion summoned with  The Earth - Hex-sealed Fusion to get an fast Amazoness Empress or Amazoness Pet Liger. Amazoness Tiger, Amazoness Sage - These cards get strong with Amazoness Queen or Amazoness Empress but are harder to play than the other Amazoness-monster-cards. Rockstone Warrior, Barrier Statue of the Drought - Good cards to get special summoned by Adamancipator Researcher, or to special summon Adamancipator Researcher, Rockstone Warrior triggers Supply Squad and gives you tokens for Link-monsters.   Extra-Deck: Amazoness Empress, Amazoness Pet Liger - High Atk Monsters with good effects that can attack all other monsters with Amazoness Call in the GY. Naturia Exterio, Naturia Beast, Coral Dragon, Stardust Dragon, Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys, Ascension Sky Dragon - the Synchro-engine that works with Adamancipator Researcher, if you have Amazoness Spy, Adamancipator Researcher and a The Earth - Hex-Sealed Fusion you can summon Naturia Exterio very fast. Stardust Dragon is easy to play because you can summon Amazoness Queen very fast, and then you only need one level-2 tuner, if you get Coral Dragon first, you need 2 tokens for Stardust Dragon, because you can not combine 2 tuners, but then you can also draw one extra card from Coral Dragon's effect. Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys is good to draw cards, you can nearly always summon it with Coral Dragon before, so even when you have only 2 Materials, you can always draw 2 cards with the effect, and get also a bit more atk then. Ascension Sky Dragon is a level-10 Synchro-Monster that can be summoned without other synchro-monsters before, and you get the material back,when he gets destroyed, which is very good with amazoness cards, the efffetcs are negated then, but Amazoness Village, Amazoness Queen, Amazoness Empress and Amazoness Onslaught still works, it is only sometimes worth and only if you have ~4 cards in the hand, so you can play it when Supply Squad triggered or when you Combo'd it with Link Burst, if it works it has better Stalling Capabilities than the other high-lvl synchro-monsters for amzoness-cards, but Stardust Dragon is always the main goal for the synchro monsters. Soul of Silvermountain, Tornado Dragon - good backup-cards with 2 level-3 or 2 level-4 cards Linkuriboh, Knightmare Phoenix, Missus Radiant, Unchained Abomination - If you have enough tokens or monsters Unchained Abomination is the strongest card to play and can destroy at least one card in every end-phase, but it can still get destroyed easier than the Amazoness-cards. Linkuribohs are good for Link Burst, it's also good to have 2, because then you can link Knightmare Phoenix and draw a card with its effect for example when you have 3 token's with the same name with Scapegoat.   Spells: Supply Squad, Amazoness Call, Link Burst, Pot Of Disparity - The draw engine, it is dependent on stalling cards which is why there are defensive spell and trap cards together with the Amazoness Cards, Supply Squad gets triggered when any monster or Token gets destroyed by battle or card effects, but only once per turn, so you don't want more than one monster to get destroyed per turn if it's possible. Pot Of Disparity is better than Pot of Extravagance, because then you can use the Link monsters more effectively, if you banish cards you can banish the backup-cards, 1 Linkuriboh, Knightmare Phoenix because it needs 2 different names as monsters, Soul of Silvermountain, Tornado Dragon, Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys and Ascension Sky Dragon Amazoness Village, Scapegoat, Swords of Revealing Light, Monster Reborn, My Body As A Shield, Raigeki, Harpie's Feather Duster - Strong defensive cards to get tokens and to support the Amazoness-engine and the Draw-engine.   Traps: Statue of Anguish Pattern, Shapesister - A defensive card that maybe triggers Supply Squad, it is a Rock-card, so you can also special summon Adamancipator Researcher with it. With Pot of Disparity Shapesister is a great card, this way you can get a fast Stardust Dragon or Naturia Beast for more negations as a support, it also can maybe trigger the destroy-effect of Statue of Anguish Pattern. Call of the Haunted - If you special summon Amazoness Princess with it you can search for another Amazoness card from the deck, and if you summon Amazoness Queen, your Amazoness-monster-cards get undestroyable. Amazoness Onslaught- The strongest trap card, because you can banish every monster you attack with Amazoness cards, works best with undestroyable Amazones-monster-cards with Amazoness Queen. You can also summon Amazoness Queen or other Amazoness-monster-cards from the hand with it. Lost Wind, Graveyard of wandering souls, Storming Mirror Force - Supportive Trap cards that support the token-engine and also the draw-engine with Graveyard of wandering souls.

deck_name: Trap Heavy Phantom Knights (With Zeus Turbo)
deck_excerpt: Trap Heavy Phantom Knights, with a Zeus engine and a Mystic Mine engine
deck_description: I had a past trap heavy phantom knights, although it didn't utilize a lot of the newer, better support, so i decided to remake it utilizing a lot of the great Phantom Rage support. So here it is, in all of it's degenerate glory. (Yes it runs Mystic Mine, don't whine about degeneracy in the comments, just run Cosmic Cyclone bro) Deck list 3x Stained Greaves- can chain onto a Boots to make a Bardiche, and can  special summon a monster from the Grave. great card 3x Ragged Gloves- pretty good starter that can buff a Break Sword to make ranking it up into Zeus easier, and can search a Boots, albeit through a complicated matter that Ash or Lock Bird adores to negate. 3x Anchient Cloak- Can be a shitty garnet but, I run at 3 because of how good it's search it. Can be a simple normal summon to use Boots or Kage on though, if you're in a tight spot 3x Torn Scales- Graveyard setup galore, which leads to searching more Boots and Fog Blades. 1x Snake boy- can't spell the name but, he's a good boy which leads to a free monster and either a draw or GY setup, or both. great card 1x Jackalope- see above 3x Kagemucha- leads to much easier XYZ in brickier hands, if you dont have a boots or something like it 3x Mystic Mine- seriously slows down the opponent and the game in general to a level that this deck likes, and then gets eradicated by Zeus 1x Terraforming- searches mystic mine lol 3x Fog Blade- easily stuns an opponent's big monster if you dont have a Mystic or if your Mystic's been eradicated. 3x Sword- Buffs your Bardiche if you leave it on the field, because im really paranoid about Bardiche being run over. 3x Mist Claws- recovers the banished PK's, to make more XYZ after you use their searches and shit that they banish themselves for 3x Fiendish Chain- does the same thing as Fog Blade 3x Trap Trick- searches a lot of your good trap's like Fog Blade that you need 3x Metaverse- same thing as Terra, just worse Extra deck list 3x Break Sword- the first monster you want to make so you can destroy cards and attack to rank up into Zeus 3x Dante- 2nd in command if all Break Sword copies are gone 3x Leviar- Good for late game recovery of resources 3x Zeus- The boss monster, really- rank it up from Break Sword and wreak havoc. 1x Bardiche- Nice option if you have a ton of dark monsters on the field and can afford to make one 1x Megaclops- good for grindier, slower games, where you might make 3 XYZ. very situational though 1x Knightmare Gryphon- good resource recovery late game Playing guide Like the original PK build I made, this isn't super complex or anything. You set up a strong backrow and Mystic Mine and then start building up an XYZ by getting out enough monsters with effects like Kage and Boots, overlay into Break Sword. Then you use Break Sword's effect to set up your graveyard and pop one of your backrows to pop the opponent's boss monster (if possible). Then you go into the battle phase, and attack with what should be a 3k Break Sword if you got Glove's boost. Afterwards, go into Main Phase 2 and rank up into Zeus. Then you wait for the opponent's turn, wipe everything they work for. Go into your turn, make more XYZ, set up more backrow if possible (don't set up another Mystic Mine, you want to just use it in the first time to slow the opponent), then wittle them down little by little as you basically Evenly Matched them with Zeus, until you eventually finish them off. (Note: Go second for this, and if your Zeus rank up gets negated/destroyed, stall the opponent with Mine and Fog Blade and Chain until you can make another Zeus, then go about the strategy i entailed above. Also, if your opponent is running heavy Mystic Mine hate, I reccomend siding it in favor of Pot of Desires and that one floodgate trap that  makes it so you cant activate spells.) Like normal, any suggestions are appeciated. Have a good day. Also, fun fact: A dude tried to fuse my Bardiche while I was in the middle of my effect when I was play testing this, then started spamming slurs when I said he couldn't do that
